tickets.description:
Hi again,

it would be useful to allow the use of the attributes
of layout \(columns, ruledLines and writtenLines\) in
subdivisions of layout \(p?, span?\).

Thus it would be possible to specify more detailed
where to a certain layout aspect applies in the codex.

Right now I have to encode:

&lt;layout columns="2-3"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;1r-v zweispaltig, 2r-10v dreispaltig.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/layout&gt;

It would be possible to write this:

&lt;layout columns="2-3"&gt;
&lt;span columns="2"&gt;1r-v zweispaltig&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span columns="3"&gt;2r-10v dreispaltig&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/layout&gt;

An even more complicated example: \(the short form
without locus and dimensions\)

&lt;layout writtenLines="35-43"&gt;Schriftraum: 
1r-202v: 19-19,5 x 10 cm, 35-37 Zeilen; 
205r-398v: 20,5-21,5 x 10-12,5cm, 38-43 Zeilen.
&lt;/layout&gt;

Here, it would be useful to be able to encode:

&lt;layout&gt;Schriftraum: 
&lt;p writtenLines="35-37"&gt;1r-202v: 19-19,5 x 10 cm,
35-37 Zeilen;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p writtenLines="38-43"&gt;205r-398v: 20,5-21,5 x
10-12,5cm, 38-43 Zeilen.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/layout&gt;


Additionally it would be helpful to have seperate
elements as well for the description of the written
space as for the way of ruling.

Greetings, Torsten Schassan

In the Menota project \(se http://www.menota.org\) we
have worked on the problem on addition, deletions etc.
what go across structural boarders. The elements
'addSpan' and 'delSpan' is available in P4 and P5, but
here are for instance no corresponding 'suppliedSpan',
'unclearSpan' to the elements 'supplied' and 'unclear'
which might also cross structural boarders. One might
argue also that there should be 'gapspan', 'sicspan',
'corrspan' and 'segspan' elements as well. In the
Menota project we have also added a new elements to
this of class elements, that is 'expunged' \(made with
the element 'del' as model, contains a letter, word or
passage expunged, marked as expunged, or otherwise
indicated as superfluous or spurious in the copy text
by the transcriber or editor. \). 

The elements for the span version of those elements
might be added to P5, but that is a lot of elements to
add to cover almost the same purpose. It might be a
simpler solution to make one generic element called
'textSpan' to cover all these cases. The name
'textSpan' is only a suggestion, as there is already an
element called 'span' in TEI, but that is to cover
something else. An attribute 'category' should be use
to indicate which type of span this is.

A tentative declaration of the generic 'textSpan'
element might be like this, using the ODD syntax for P5:

&lt;elementSpec ident="textSpan" mode="add"&gt;
&lt;desc&gt;2004.11.28 TMB: new element defined. The
element is based on the element TEI 'addSpan'
with an extra attribute 'category', and to
encode a generic span of text that might be
added, deleted etc. This element is a milestone. 
The element is made to avoid to make a
series of 'delSpan', 'suppliedSpan'etc.&lt;/desc&gt;
&lt;classes&gt;
&lt;memberOf key="tei.editIncl" /&gt;
&lt;/classes&gt;
&lt;content&gt;
&lt;rng:empty/&gt;
&lt;/content&gt;
&lt;attList&gt;
&lt;attDef ident="category" usage="opt"&gt;
&lt;datatype&gt;
&lt;rng:text /&gt;
&lt;/datatype&gt;
&lt;valList type="open"&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="add" /&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="del" /&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="supplied" /&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="expunged" /&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="unclear" /&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="gap" /&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="seg" /&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="sic" /&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="corr" /&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="other" /&gt;
&lt;/valList&gt;

&lt;/attDef&gt;
&lt;\!-- Here follows the same attributes as
used in addSpan --&gt;
&lt;/attList&gt;
&lt;/elementSpec&gt;         

It could then be used in the same way is indicated in
the TEI Guideline for 'addSpan' and 'delSpan'.

Any comments are welcome on this subject.

