&lt;msIdentifier&gt;
has a hard-wired dependence on elements from the
namesdates module, which seems unwise and unncessary. I
believe that the following content model would be 
a suitable replacement with an acceptable degree of
looseness.

&lt;content&gt;
&lt;rng:group&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:group&gt;
&lt;rng:ref
name="model.placeLike\_sequenceOptional"/&gt;
&lt;rng:optional&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="institution"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:optional&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="repository"/&gt;
&lt;rng:optional&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="collection"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:optional&gt;
&lt;rng:optional&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="idno"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:optional&gt;
&lt;/rng:group&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="msName"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="altIdentifier"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="msName"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;/rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;/rng:group&gt;
&lt;/content&gt;

Currently there is little clear indication on how the
expanded portions of an abbreviation are meant to be
indicated inside an &lt;expan&gt; element. There is some
discussion at 6.5.5 and 18.1.2. This is needed as many
people wish to indicate just those letters which have
been supplied.  

Previously on TEI-L, I believe &lt;hi&gt; has been suggested
for this use, but this is semantically wrong since it
is not highlighted text in the original.  The use of
&lt;seg&gt; is a possibility, but a bulky one.  &lt;supplied&gt; is
clearly wrong because of its definition \(though that
could be changed\).

One possibility is to use a nested &lt;expan&gt;.  Since
&lt;expan&gt; is defined as containing "the expansion of an
abbreviation", this is arguably correct.  Though, I
believe it has been suggested previously that this
should only be used for the expansion as a whole.  But
if we did that it would mean something like this:

&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;abbr&gt;dni&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;expan&gt;d&lt;expan&gt;omi&lt;/expan&gt;ni&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;

Though I don't really like that, I prefer it to using
&lt;seg&gt;:

&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;abbr&gt;dni&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;expan&gt;d&lt;seg type="expansion"&gt;omi&lt;/seg&gt;ni&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;

What about the possibility of a new element existing
solely as a child of &lt;expan&gt; to indicate the individual
expanded letters of an abbreviation.  For example: 

&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;abbr&gt;dni&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;expan&gt;d&lt;e&gt;omi&lt;/e&gt;ni&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;


-James

We need a designated place in the header to record pointers to or embed additional metadata.

By this I mean that I want to be able to have a TEI wrapper element where it is understood that the content will either be pointers to external schemas, ODDs, etc. or that they will be embedded \(in their own namespaces and with appropriate changes to the ODD/schema\) inside this element.

This should not just be for schema-related additional metadata, but a generalised element for other forms of metadata not covered by \(or probably of interest to\) the TEI.

So this could just be \(assuming different names\):

&lt;metadata&gt;
&lt;ptr type="ODD" target="http://domain.com/MyTEIODD.xml"/&gt;
&lt;ptr type="RNG" target="http://domain.com/MyTEIODD.rng"/&gt;
&lt;/metadata&gt;

Or could actually embed the RNG in at that point \(with changes to the ODD which validates it\)

Equally it could contain other namespaced elements.  For example, the AHDS Common Metadata Framework, or METS profiles, etc.

-James

One can find in manuscript descriptions more than one list with bibliographical items, e.g. to distinguish between editions and other literature. Therefore it might be reasonable to change the definition of &lt;additional&gt; from

element additional
\{
att.global.attributes,
\( adminInfo?, surrogates?, listBibl? \)
\}


to

element additional
\{
att.global.attributes,
\( adminInfo?, surrogates?, listBibl\* \)
\}

