Martin Mueller initiated this  thread at  http://listserv.brown.edu/archives/cgi-bin/wa?A2=ind0803&L=TEI-L&T=0&F=&S=&P=1263

.. I have a question about the &lt;sp&gt; element and wonder why it cannot  
directly contain &lt;q&gt;, &lt;quote&gt;, or &lt;floatingText&gt; elements.  The major  
use of the &lt;sp&gt; element, I assume, is to enclose utterances by  
speakers in plays. So a play is articulated into acts, scenes, and  
speeches. Here is an example from Cymbeline:

Soothsayer \[reads\] When as a lion's whelp . . . . flourish in peace  
and plenty

Thou, Leonatus, art the lion's whelp
The fit and apt construction of thy name

So we have a speaker label, a stage direction, a reading of an  
"external" document in prose, followed by the Soothsayer's comments in  
verse.

This could be represented as

&lt;sp&gt;&lt;speaker&gt;Soothsayer&lt;/speaker&gt;
&lt;stage&gt; reads&lt;/stage&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;quote&gt;&lt;floatingText&gt;&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When as a lion's whelp . . . . flourish in peace and plenty&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/floatingText&gt;&lt;/quote&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;l&gt;Thou Leonatus, ar the lion's whelp&lt;/l&gt;
&lt;l&gt;The fit and apt construction of thy name&lt;/l&gt;
&lt;/sp&gt;

Perhaps &lt;floatingText&gt; is too heavy artillery for a very short, though  
complete, document,  and just &lt;quote&gt; or &lt;quote type="oracle"&gt; would  
do.  But why not admit

&lt;sp&gt;&lt;speaker&gt;Soothsayer&lt;/speaker&gt;
&lt;stage&gt; reads&lt;/stage&gt;
&lt;quote&gt;When as a lion's whelp . . . . flourish in peace and plenty&lt;/ 
quote&gt;
&lt;l&gt;Thou Leonatus, art the lion's whelp&lt;/l&gt;
&lt;l&gt;The fit and apt construction of thy name&lt;/l&gt;
&lt;/sp&gt;

It is a flatter structure than

&lt;sp&gt;&lt;speaker&gt;Soothsayer&lt;/speaker&gt;
&lt;stage&gt; reads&lt;/stage&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;quote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When as a lion's whelp . . . . flourish in peace and plenty&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/quote&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;l&gt;Thou Leonatus, ar the lion's whelp&lt;/l&gt;
&lt;l&gt;The fit and apt construction of thy name&lt;/l&gt;

and other things being equal, flatter is better.

