My instinct is that the mechanism demonstrated in aphrodisias2.xml is fine. I have replicated the relevant bits, below, for those who don't want to delve into the repository.

I think, in general, TEI users wish to be told what kind structures to put information in and point to. However, it may be reasonable to wish to apply named time periods to other structures. E.g., it might make sense for period= to point to a &lt;when&gt; in a &lt;timeline&gt;.

So I think the Guidelines should suggest that period= point to a &lt;category&gt; in a &lt;taxonomy type="periods"&gt;, and should show an example of such, I don't think they should require that.

relevant bits of aphrodisias2.xml
\-------- ---- -- ----------------
&lt;\!-- in TEI/teiHeader/encodingDesc: --&gt;
&lt;classDecl&gt;
&lt;taxonomy xml:id="periods"&gt;
&lt;category xml:id="hellenistic"&gt;
&lt;catDesc&gt;
&lt;ref target="http://www.wikipedia.com/wiki/Hellenistic"
&gt;Hellenistic&lt;/ref&gt;. Commonly treated as &lt;date
notBefore="-0323" notAfter="-0031"/&gt;.
&lt;/catDesc&gt;
&lt;/category&gt;
&lt;category xml:id="roman"&gt;
&lt;catDesc&gt;
&lt;ref target="http://www.wikipedia.com/wiki/Roman\_Empire"
&gt;Roman&lt;/ref&gt;
&lt;/catDesc&gt;
&lt;/category&gt;
&lt;category xml:id="christian"&gt;
&lt;catDesc&gt; The Christian period technically starts at the
birth of Jesus, but in
practice is considered to date from the conversion of Constantine
in &lt;date when="0312"&gt;312 AD&lt;/date&gt;. &lt;/catDesc&gt;
&lt;/category&gt;
&lt;/taxonomy&gt;
&lt;/classDecl&gt;
&lt;\!-- somewhere in a &lt;p&gt; descendant of &lt;text&gt;: --&gt;
The city was later
renamed &lt;placeName period="\#christian"
&gt;Stauropolis&lt;/placeName&gt; \(Σταυρούπολις 'city of the
cross'\) in the Christian era.

