tickets.description:
In order to be allowed to supply more than one range of locus information in the beginning of a msItem we would like to see a &lt;locusGrp&gt; element which would contain more than one locus element.

Example:
Bl. 13--26, 37--58, 82--96 Stücke von Daniel Ecklin’s Reise ins h. Land; \[...\]

would result in
&lt;msItem&gt;
&lt;locusGrp&gt;
&lt;locus&gt;Bl. 13--26&lt;/locus&gt;
&lt;locus&gt;37--58&lt;/locus&gt;
&lt;locus&gt;82--96&lt;/locus&gt;
&lt;/locusGrp&gt;
&lt;note&gt;Stücke von Daniel Ecklin’s Reise ins h. Land&lt;note&gt;
&lt;/msItem&gt;

Accordingly, the definition of msItem has to be changed:

\(
\(locusGrp | locus\)?,
\(
model.pLike+
| \( model.titlepagePart | model.msItemPart | model.global \)+
\)
\)


Note: locusGrp might be useful in other places like decoNote but probably not everywhere.

posts.text:
Presumably the &lt;locusGrp&gt; element should be repeatable? and it should have a @scheme attribut which its child &lt;locus&gt; elements will all inherit? Then you can have a discontinuous sequences of pages with two different foliations:
&lt;locusGrp scheme="\#a"&gt;
&lt;locus from="f1" to "f4"/&gt;
&lt;locus from="f8" to "f9"/&gt;
&lt;/locusGrp&gt;
&lt;locusGrp scheme="\#b"&gt;
&lt;locus from="p3" to "p5"/&gt;
&lt;locus from="p44" to "p48"/&gt;
&lt;/locusGrp&gt;

I think it would be a good thing to have &lt;locusGrp&gt; not only for expressing one case of grouping discontinuous ranges, but also, eventually, to group various loci in different ways according to the scope of the analysis.

The example in the guidelines about foliation may be one case:
&lt;locusGrp target="\#item1"&gt;
&lt;locus scheme="\#original"&gt;XCIII&lt;/locus&gt;
&lt;locus scheme="\#modern"&gt;135&lt;/locus&gt;
&lt;/locusGrp&gt;

So what I am saying is that may be it will be too limiting to allow the use of &lt;locusGrp&gt; ONLY for discontinuous ranges.

Torsten suggests it may also be useful within &lt;decoNote&gt; and I would say, what about &lt;handNote&gt; too then?

See for instance the example at http://www.diamm.ac.uk/jsp/Source.jsp?navToggle=1&sourceKey=805

The fourth paragraph contains some notes on a specific scribe who contributed to other manuscripts too.

This is just to say that I am in favour of this new element, but may be we need to think more of where else it would be useful and what attributes to supply it with.

&gt; I must say I find the idea that &lt;corr/&gt; means
&gt; &lt;suppressed&gt;xxxx&lt;/suppressed&gt; somewhat unintuitive. 

But it doesn't. &lt;choice&gt;&lt;sic&gt;xxxxx&lt;/sic&gt;&lt;corr/&gt;&lt;/choice&gt; does.

Seems to me &lt;suppressed&gt;xxxx&lt;/suppressed&gt; means “the editor \(indicated by resp=, I presume\) is indicating that for some processes the content ‘xxxx’ should be ignored” Seems to me the same semantics are indicated with
&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;sic&gt;xxxxx&lt;/sic&gt;
&lt;corr/&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;
which means “the editor \(indicated by resp=\) is indicating that for some processes the content ‘xxxx’ should be replaced by the content ‘’”.

Seems to me if &lt;suppressed&gt; \(or &lt;suppress&gt;\) is added to the Guidelines, it would be as syntactic sugar for &lt;choice&gt; with &lt;sic&gt; and empty &lt;corr&gt;. \(This may not be a bad thing, of course. And the idea that &lt;sic&gt; would have a fix="suppress" may be more coherent syntactic sugar.\)

Why do we have an element &lt;supplied&gt; at all if this is syntactic sugar for
&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;sic/&gt;
&lt;corr&gt;xxxxx&lt;/corr&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;?

Is the discussion all about preventing to invent a new element? In that case we should remove &lt;supplied&gt;. ;-\)
To be serious: You might disagree on my statement that an empty element might not be good style of encoding but this was the "result" of a discussion on tei-ms-l that &lt;choice&gt;&lt;sic&gt;xxx&lt;/sic&gt;&lt;corr/&gt;&lt;/choice&gt; is \*not\* equal to &lt;suppressed&gt;xxx&lt;/suppressed&gt;.

PS @Syd: I am talking about the Manuscript SIG meeting in London where we used on of the sessions not only to discuss things but submit "results" immediately as SourceForge items.

Why do we have an element &lt;supplied&gt; at all if this is syntactic sugar for
&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;sic/&gt;
&lt;corr&gt;xxxxx&lt;/corr&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;?

Is the discussion all about preventing to invent a new element? In that case we should remove &lt;supplied&gt;. ;-\)
To be serious: You might disagree on my statement that an empty element might not be good style of encoding but this was the "result" of a discussion on tei-ms-l that &lt;choice&gt;&lt;sic&gt;xxx&lt;/sic&gt;&lt;corr/&gt;&lt;/choice&gt; is \*not\* equal to &lt;suppressed&gt;xxx&lt;/suppressed&gt;.

PS @Syd: I am talking about the Manuscript SIG meeting in London where we used on of the sessions not only to discuss things but submit "results" immediately as SourceForge items.

&gt; Why do we have an element &lt;supplied&gt; at all if this is syntactic sugar for
&gt; &lt;choice&gt;
&gt;   &lt;sic/&gt;
&gt;   &lt;corr&gt;xxxxx&lt;/corr&gt;
&gt; &lt;/choice&gt;?

Ah, good question. I think the answer is because it isn't. The above construct is what I \(the editor\) use if I believe there is an apparent error that consists of a missing “xxxxx”. The construct &lt;supplied&gt;xxxxx&lt;/supplied&gt; is what I use if I wish to insert an “xxxxx” for some other reason, typically because my source is illegible due to being damaged, a poor photocopy, or miserable handwriting, or some such.

So one could argue that &lt;supplied reason="apparent error"&gt;xxxxx&lt;/supplied&gt; is syntactic sugar for &lt;choice&gt;&lt;sic/&gt;&lt;corr&gt;xxxxx&lt;/corr&gt;&lt;/choice&gt;, but that doesn't let us eliminate any of the involved elements, and I don't think it makes the encoding system simpler, myself.

&gt; Syd: I am talking about the Manuscript SIG meeting in London …
Thanks\! Sorry I missed that meeting, but can only be in one place at a time. Sigh.

Two thoughts jump to mind. First, it is worth pointing out that in the example Peter provides text content is put at the same "level" as element content, which most of us find distirbing. So I would suggest instead 
&lt;author&gt;
&lt;idno type="nldai"&gt;info:eu-repo/dai/nl/12456454&lt;/idno&gt;
&lt;idno type="openid"&gt; https://me.yahoo.com/johndoe61&lt;/idno&gt;
&lt;persName&gt;John Doe&lt;/persName&gt;
&lt;/author&gt;

But more importantly, before you permit &lt;idno&gt; in the innards of &lt;author&gt;, &lt;editor&gt;, &lt;publisher&gt;, etc., I'd like to know know what are the explicit semantics? Problematic to just say "an identifier for the thingy indicated by the parent element", because the parent is canonically &lt;publicationStmt&gt;.

Also I'm also a little worried about what multiple occurrences mean. Are the two &lt;idno&gt;s in the above example alternative identifiers of the same author \(in this case a person\)? Or are there three authors? If the answer to you is immediately obvious "alternative", think about the analagous cases:

&lt;author&gt;
&lt;persName type="common"&gt;Peter Boot&lt;/persName&gt;
&lt;persName type="regularized"&gt;Boot, Dr. Peter&lt;/persName&gt;
&lt;persName xml:lang="es"&gt;Pedro Cargador&lt;/persName&gt;
&lt;/author&gt;
vs.
&lt;author&gt;
&lt;persName&gt;Syd Bauman&lt;/persName&gt;
&lt;persName&gt;Peter Boot&lt;/persName&gt;
&lt;persName&gt;Kevin Hawkins&lt;/perssName&gt;
&lt;/author&gt;

The Guidelines license the multiple authors in one &lt;author&gt; approach.

