Hi all,

I'd like to suggest adding a @scope attribute to &lt;rendition/&gt; which allows specification of CSS pseudo-elements, in order to more fully utilize the expressive ability of CSS in TEI. These pseudo-elements are used to target styling for only a portion of the given text. For example, there is a 'first-letter' pseudo-element to target styling of the first letter in the targeted element, while there are the useful "before" and "after" pseudo-elements, used often in conjunction with the "content" property to add some styling characters \(Unicode provides quite a few\) before or after the element.

For example, the CSS "first-letter" pseudo-element might be encoded under this proposal as follows:

&lt;rendition xml:id="dropcaps" scope="first-letter" scheme="css"&gt;font-size:xx-large&lt;/rendition&gt;
...
&lt;p rendition="\#dropcaps"&gt;Once upon a time...&lt;/p&gt;

The "O" in "Once" would thus be indicated as having drop-caps in the original \(and stylesheets could use this information in a predictable and standard way to create such drop-caps\). This would not rely on "hacks" such as using XSLT to extract pseudo-element information added within &lt;rendition&gt;

The above would also solve the current need for relying on the non-CSS PRE or POST convention \(as used in your default stylesheets\) for specifying use of different quotation marks without actually encoding them in the text \(:before and :after pseudo-elements could be used under @scope in conjunction with the 'content' property\).

&lt;rendition xml:id="quoteBefore" scheme="css" scope="before"&gt;content: '"';&lt;/rendition&gt;
&lt;rendition xml:id="quoteAfter" scheme="css" scope="after"&gt;content: '"';&lt;/rendition&gt;
...
&lt;p rendition="\#quoteBefore \#quoteAfter"&gt;Four score and seven years ago...&lt;/p&gt;

\(The above adds quotation marks--which could instead be curly ones, etc.--at the beginning and end of the paragraph.\)

I think this would further build on TEI's advantages in offering to fully allow rendering information of the original to be encoded but while allowing for sufficient separation so that reproducers can choose whether to replicate these features in their own version or not \(e.g., in the proposed system, a reproducer could more easily change the style of quotation marks\).

\(as proposed on the tei-ms-sig: http://listserv.brown.edu/archives/cgi-bin/wa?A2=ind0811&L=tei-ms-sig&T=0&F=&S=&P=68\)

I think we need slightly to loosen up the content model of &lt; dimensions &gt;.

At present the model is \(compact\): \( height?, width?, depth? \); in other words, optional &lt; height &gt; \*followed by\* optional &lt; width &gt; \*followed by\* optional &lt; depth &gt;. I have three suggestions to make here:

\(1\) allow these elements in any order, since processing can easily pull the correct values out anyway;

\(2\) add a fourth dimension, &lt; diameter &gt; for objects with a circular face;

\(3\) allow a generic or miscellaneous measurement element \(perhaps even &lt; measure &gt;, of which I would have assumed height, width, and depth were in a sense specializations anyway\) for other dimensions that might occasionally be needed but are not common enough \(or predictable enough\) to warrant an element of their own. \(In at least one case we have needed to tag the circumference of an object.\)

posts.text:
how about @fromPage and @toPage \(and no content\): like
&lt;biblScope fromPage="1" toPage="23"/&gt;
as an alternative to
&lt;biblScope type="pp"&gt;1-23&lt;/biblScope&gt;
or \(I suppose\)
&lt;biblScope fromPage="1" toPage="23"&gt;pp 1-23&lt;/biblScope&gt;
This leaves open the question of what to do in the case of inconsistency:
&lt;biblScope fromPage="1" toPage="23"&gt;pp 1-233&lt;/biblScope&gt;

I'm going to revise my earlier opinion to support adding @valueType to &lt;num&gt;. It would in fact allow a great many numeric values to be captured in a simple way. For example:

&lt;p&gt;The computer gave a cryptic response: &lt;q&gt;&lt;num type="binary" value="42" valueType="decimal"&gt;101010&lt;/num&gt;\!&lt;/q&gt;, it shouted.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He owned &lt;num value="2/3" valueType="fraction"&gt;2/3&lt;/num&gt; of the property.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Has Google actually indexed &lt;num value="1E100" valueType="float"&gt; one googol&lt;/num&gt; Web pages yet?&lt;/p&gt;

\(In the first example, @type applies to the element content, @valueType to the content of @value. We would need to make this distinction clear in the documentation.\)

The easiest thing for us to do would be to \(1\) add @valueType as an optional attribute \(and make explicit that if there is no @valueType, then any @value is interpreted as decimal\), and \(2\) provide a suggested list of @valueType values \(decimal, fraction, float, hex, octal, binary ... ?\) and examples of usage.

\*Constraining\* usages would be much trickier, and I don't believe it is possible in RELAX NG as the legal patterns for @val would depend on the declared @valueType. But one could write Schematron rules to enforce the syntax of known patterns.

tickets.description:
It'd be really cool if relatedItem had @target so that it could point. 

&lt; related item target="\#moser2001"&gt;
&lt;bibl&gt;Moser 2001 &lt;biblScope&gt;pp. 53-71&lt;/biblScope&gt;
&lt; /relatedItem&gt;

The rationale for this is that relatedItem has inherently pointer-esque qualities. If we were starting from a blank state, we might have done this instead of allowing ref and ptr as children.

@target would be optional, since relatedItem can contain the bibliography of the related item.

posts.text:
I agree with the either/or: @target is for the simple cases, if you want more, you use the content. 

Here are two examples:
&lt;biblStruct xml:id="burke001"&gt;
&lt;monogr&gt;
&lt;author&gt;Burke, Peter&lt;/author&gt;
&lt;title&gt;Culture and society in Renaissance Italy, 1420-1540&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;imprint&gt;
&lt;pubPlace&gt;London&lt;/pubPlace&gt;
&lt;publisher&gt;Batsford&lt;/publisher&gt;
&lt;date&gt;1972&lt;/date&gt;
&lt;/imprint&gt;
&lt;/monogr&gt;
&lt;/biblStruct&gt;
&lt;biblStruct xml:id="burke002"&gt;
&lt;monogr&gt;
&lt;author&gt;Burke, Peter&lt;/author&gt;
&lt;title&gt;The Italian Renaissance : culture and society in Italy&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;edition&gt;Revised edition&lt;/edition&gt;
&lt;imprint&gt;
&lt;pubPlace&gt;Cambridge&lt;/pubPlace&gt;
&lt;publisher&gt;Polity Press&lt;/publisher&gt;
&lt;date&gt;1987&lt;/date&gt;
&lt;/imprint&gt;
&lt;/monogr&gt;
&lt;relatedItem type="revisionOf" target="\#burke002"/&gt;
&lt;/biblStruct&gt;
&lt;biblStruct xml:id="burke003"&gt;
&lt;monogr&gt;
&lt;author&gt;Burke, Peter&lt;/author&gt;
&lt;title&gt;De Italiaanse renaissance&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;editor role="translator"&gt;Engelsman, Jaap&lt;/editor&gt;
&lt;edition&gt;Tweede druk&lt;/edition&gt;
&lt;imprint&gt;
&lt;pubPlace&gt;Amsterdam&lt;/pubPlace&gt;
&lt;publisher&gt;Agon&lt;/publisher&gt;
&lt;date&gt;1992&lt;/date&gt;
&lt;/imprint&gt;
&lt;/monogr&gt;
&lt;relatedItem type="translationOf" target="\#burke002"/&gt;
&lt;/biblStruct&gt;

Let me just register some issues that come to mind. I'm not trying to say that this is a bad idea -- I can see its advantages. But there some things that make it potentially troublesome, some of them more serious, some less.

\* technically, I think it would be better to come up with two new namespaces \(multiplied by the number of languages used\) in the wiki, rather than with the sort of nested subdocuments that you propose; at least searching may be easier;
\* I'm somewhat concerned with the persistence of valid information: there is no active wiki community, which would clean up such pages after an upgrade of the Guidelines; it is hard to expect whoever fixes/expands something in the Guidelines to edit the corresponding wiki pages; the potential result being that the content of the wiki pages may quickly become misleading wrt the content of the given element definition/description;
\* the proposed naming of the chapter/section-related pages exposes the internal naming used in the Guidelines, to no obvious advantage; if at all, it might make sense to have a single wiki page per chapter, with subsections, in that wiki page, for subsections in the given chapter, with full subsection titles rather than IDs; but still the previous point applies here;

This kind of Web 2.0 extensions needs an active community already at the beginning, because it is increasingly difficult to clean up accumulated editorial mess. I don't see such a community in our wiki, and I am not really convinced that providing wiki links in this manner is a way to extend it.

I have worked with medieval texts where almost al words are in some way abbreviated. This makes the text almost unreadable for the editor. I sympathise with the request. But maybe we need to figure out exactly how we would use it. 

So in your text you would have something like 

... the &lt;anchor xml:id="a1"/&gt;W3C&lt;anchor xml:id="a2"/&gt; states ...

and in the 'apparatus', somewhere else:

&lt;choice from="\#a1" to="\#a2"&gt;
&lt;abbr&gt;W3C&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;expan&gt;World Wide Web Consortium&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;

Or perhaps rather this:

In the text

... the &lt;abbr xml:id="a1"/&gt;W3C&lt;/abbr&gt; states ...

and in the 'apparatus', somewhere else:

&lt;choice from="\#a1"&gt;
&lt;expan&gt;World Wide Web Consortium&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;

The first solution implies duplication of the abbreviated text. It doesn't keep the text free of clutter. The second solution seems cleaner to me. 

One way of having the main text completely uncluttered would be 

In the main text:

&lt;p xml:id="p1"&gt; ... the W3C states ... &lt;/p&gt;

and in the 'apparatus', somewhere else:

&lt;choice from="string-range\(\#p1,30,3\)"&gt;
&lt;abbr&gt;W3C&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;expan&gt;World Wide Web Consortium&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;

\(where '30' is the offset of 'W3C' in the paragraph.

| ... the &lt;abbr xml:id="a1"&gt;W3C&lt;/abbr&gt; states ...
| and in the 'apparatus', somewhere else:
| &lt;choice from="\#a1"&gt;
|  &lt;expan&gt;World Wide Web Consortium&lt;/expan&gt;
| &lt;/choice&gt;

It is worth noting that TEI already supports this mechanism using exclude=. \(And people dislike it so much we came up with &lt;choice&gt;-in-place instead.\)

... the &lt;abbr xml:id="a1" exclude="\#e1"&gt;W3C&lt;/abbr&gt; states ...

and in the 'apparatus', somewhere else:

&lt;expan xml:id="e1" exclude="\#a1"&gt;World Wide Web Consortium&lt;/expan&gt;

Peter has the following examples:
&lt;quote&gt;
... the &lt;anchor xml:id="a1"/&gt;W3C&lt;anchor xml:id="a2"/&gt; states ...

and in the 'apparatus', somewhere else:

&lt;choice from="\#a1" to="\#a2"&gt;
&lt;abbr&gt;W3C&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;expan&gt;World Wide Web Consortium&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;

Or perhaps rather this:

In the text

... the &lt;abbr xml:id="a1"/&gt;W3C&lt;/abbr&gt; states ...

and in the 'apparatus', somewhere else:

&lt;choice from="\#a1"&gt;
&lt;expan&gt;World Wide Web Consortium&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;
&lt;/quote&gt;
I quite like the second one, of which I did not think.  However, in that case, one could maybe use the @target attribute, rather than @from.  I would still like to see @from and @to for cases such as the first, where the encoder would like to have both values in the appendix.

tickets.description:
At the moment, the only way to point to a constrained list of materials from the objectDesc section of the header, using the @material attribute on supportDesc:

&lt;supportDesc material="marble"&gt;

Given that there is also a 'material' element that can appear inside &lt;support&gt;, it would sometimes make more sense to have an @ref attribute \(aut sim.\) on that element from which we can point to the taxonomy, especially if the object has more than one material, for example, or there is some uncertainty about the material, etc.

This would then allow formulations such as:

&lt;support&gt;&lt;material ref="\#marble"&gt;white marble&lt;/material&gt; chased with &lt;material ref="\#lead"&gt;black lead&lt;/material&gt;&lt;/support&gt;

posts.text:
The request is for an element parallel with &lt;material&gt; \(including the addition of @ref as discussed in 2811234\). Like &lt;material&gt;, it would be a child of &lt;support&gt;. It would enable smaller granularity of description than is enabled by using @form on &lt;objectDesc&gt;. The example of &lt;support&gt; from the guidelines:

&lt;objectDesc form="roll"&gt;
&lt;supportDesc&gt;
&lt;support&gt; Parchment roll with &lt;material&gt;silk&lt;/material&gt; ribbons.
&lt;/support&gt;
&lt;/supportDesc&gt;
&lt;/objectDesc&gt; 

Would be:

&lt;objectDesc&gt;
&lt;supportDesc&gt;
&lt;support&gt; &lt;material&gt;Parchment&lt;material&gt; &lt;object&gt;roll&lt;object&gt; with &lt;material&gt;silk&lt;/material&gt; &lt;object&gt;ribbons&lt;object&gt;.
&lt;/support&gt;
&lt;/supportDesc&gt;
&lt;/objectDesc&gt; 

cf. 2811234: @ref would be available on both &lt;material&gt; and &lt;object&gt;, so the instances in the &lt;support&gt; prose could point to a list existing elsewhere.

In general, I think I'm in favor of &lt;object&gt; with ref= on both &lt;object&gt; and &lt;support&gt; \(which perhaps should be &lt;objectType&gt; and &lt;madeOf&gt;\). This would permit
\_&lt;support&gt;
\_\_\_&lt;object&gt;roll&lt;/object&gt;
\_\_\_&lt;material&gt;parchment&lt;/material&gt;
\_&lt;/support&gt;
somewhat different than
\_&lt;support&gt;
\_\_\_&lt;object&gt;roll&lt;/object&gt;
\_\_\_&lt;material&gt;paper towel&lt;/material&gt;
\_&lt;/support&gt;

But the discussion brings up a potential problem. Again playing devil’s advocate: doesn’t this example \(from the &lt;support&gt; and &lt;supportDesc&gt; tagdocs\) imply that there is writing on the silk ribbon?

I don't think hte example provided by "nobody" in the logic of the TEI modularisation: I would expect multiple &lt;object&gt;s inside &lt;objectDesc&gt; and within these &lt;supportDesc&gt; with possible multiple &lt;supports&gt;\! 
\[Whenever we come across a &lt;...Desc&gt; in TEI, the same element is used as child\! \]
The @form would have to be moved to the &lt;object&gt; then?

&lt;objectDesc&gt;
&lt;object form="roll"&gt;
&lt;supportDesc&gt;
&lt;support&gt; &lt;material&gt;Parchment&lt;material&gt; &lt;term&gt;roll&lt;term&gt;&lt;/support&gt;
&lt;/supportDesc&gt;
&lt;/object&gt;
&lt;object form="ribbon"&gt;
&lt;supportDesc&gt;
&lt;support&gt;with &lt;material&gt;silk&lt;/material&gt; &lt;term&gt;ribbons&lt;term&gt;&lt;/support&gt;
&lt;/supportDesc&gt;
&lt;/object&gt;
&lt;/objectDesc&gt;

tickets.description:
Version: tei-xsl 5.24


Description:

If the user wants to produce a document with a page size other than the default \(e.g. Letter\), he must not only override the "latexGeometryOptions" parameter but also the "latexPageSize" template.  Just setting latexGeometryOptions results in an odd-looking document.

I found that the following overrides allow me to produce a good-looking document:

&lt;xsl:param name="latexGeometryOptions" select="'letterpaper,centering'"/&gt;
&lt;xsl:template name="latexPaperSize"&gt;
&lt;/xsl:template&gt;

This suggests that maybe "latexPaperSize" should be empty by default rather than contain measurements for A4 paper size.  I do not know the issue well enough to tell whether leaving "latexPaperSize" empty is a better default.

If "latexPaperSize" cannot be empty by default then there may be a way to generate an error to the user if latexGeometryOptions is overriden but latexPaperSize is left as is.

I believe @cert or better att.editLike attributes should be allowed on model.choicePart  \(and choice itself\) as you way wish to indicate the certainty of any of these elements inside a choice relative to each other. Some of model.choicePart \(such as expan\) are already memebers of att.editLike, but these attributes would be equally useful on those which are not.
i.e.

&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;abbr cert="high"&gt;I really think it says that&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;abbr cert="low"&gt;There is a vague possibility it says this other thing&lt;/abbr&gt; 
&lt;expan cert="high"&gt;The probable expansion&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;expan cert="low"&gt;The unlikely expansion&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;

or:

&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;choice cert="high"&gt;
&lt;abbr&gt;I really think it says that&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;expan&gt;The probable expansion&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;
&lt;choice cert="low"&gt;
&lt;abbr&gt;There is a vague possibility it says this other thing&lt;/abbr&gt; 
&lt;expan&gt;The unlikely expansion&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;

posts.text:
"The starred ones are not currently members of att.editLike, presumably on
the grounds that there's not much scope for uncertainty about marking
something as a seg, orig, abbr or sic: they're all supposed to be used for
non-controversial items."

This is the bit of the way that they are envisioned that I'm disagreeing with.  I think one can transcribe an abbreviation and be uncertain about whether the transcription is accurate.  Likewise, the original might be the expansion.:

&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;expan&gt;North Atlantic Treaty Organization&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;abbr cert="low"&gt;NorATO&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;abbr cert="high"&gt;NATO&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;

If it isn't intended that we can provide a choice between multiples of all of the model.choicePart members, then why-oh-why are they repeatable?   \(In fact a good customisation example might be to make them not repeatable, and to have schematron rules enforce 'if you have &lt;sic&gt; you must have &lt;corr&gt;' or something similar to show how to do this \(\*note to self\*\)\) 

In saying all members of this class should also be members of the attribute class, I wasn't really meaning it as said.  I meant each individual element which the TEI happens to already have in choicePart should be a member of editLike. \(And I'd want to include choice as well\).  However, being able to have class dependencies based not just on particular elements or attributes, but on macros and class membership does seem like an attractive thing to have in ODD2. Maybe make a note of it at http://wiki.tei-c.org/index.php/ODD-dev ?

I can envision use cases where I would want multiple &lt;orig&gt; elements to express potential alternative transcriptions, \(and same with seg, abbr, sic, and choice\). Or indeed, where I might want a &lt;choice&gt; between multiple &lt;abbr&gt; elements one of which I'm more confident about my reading, and not provide an expansion.

If &lt;choice&gt; isn't meant to be used this way then it should be more explicitly noted in discussion and reference pages.  

-James

Some remarks:

1\. we should distinguish between certainty of an abbreviation \(is this really an abbreviation?\) and certainty of the transcription. In the case of James' example:  

&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;expan&gt;North Atlantic Treaty Organization&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;abbr cert="low"&gt;NorATO&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;abbr cert="high"&gt;NATO&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;

it seems to me the more correct  encoding would be 

&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;expan&gt;North Atlantic Treaty Organization&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;abbr&gt;
&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;seg cert="low"&gt;NorATO&lt;/seg&gt;
&lt;seg cert="high"&gt;NATO&lt;/seg&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;
&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;

This would imply the need for @cert on seg

2\. The first example in the original request seems inadvisable to me: 

&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;abbr cert="high"&gt;I really think it says that&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;abbr cert="low"&gt;There is a vague possibility it says this other
thing&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;expan cert="high"&gt;The probable expansion&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;expan cert="low"&gt;The unlikely expansion&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;

This leaves implicit which of the abbr's and expan's should be paired together.
The second example 

&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;choice cert="high"&gt;
&lt;abbr&gt;I really think it says that&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;expan&gt;The probable expansion&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;
&lt;choice cert="low"&gt;
&lt;abbr&gt;There is a vague possibility it says this other thing&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;expan&gt;The unlikely expansion&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;

is in this respect unambiguous. This argues for @cert on choice. 

3\. From these examples, I see a reason to make @cert available on seg and on choice. 

4\. However, James asks for '@cert or better att.editLike attributes'. But why, if we need only @cert, should we make the other, clearly irrelevant, attributes in att.editLike \(att.dimensions and att.ranging\) available? Why not stick with att.responsibility? 

5\. In sum: my proposal would be to add choice and seg to att.responsibility

Peter: I think you are missing the point of being able to repeat multiple &lt;abbr&gt;s &lt;corr&gt;s, &lt;expan&gt;s  etc. inside one choice. Yes, I could nest choice as you suggest, but that presupposes making one particular pairing between these... which I don't think we should necessarily force users to do. If we have:  

&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;abbr cert="high"&gt;I really think it says that&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;abbr cert="low"&gt;There is a vague possibility it says this other thing&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;expan cert="high"&gt;The probable expansion&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;expan cert="low"&gt;The unlikely expansion&lt;/expan&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;

I might for some unknown reason want to pair the &lt;abbr cert="low"&gt; with the &lt;expan cert="high"&gt;.  Having to fragment this into nested choices means either choosing such pairings in advance, or producing redundant nested choices with \*all\* possibilities. 

-James

To play devil’s advocate, I’m going to posit that Elena’s example is an argument for permitting \*either\* &lt;add&gt; \*or\* &lt;del&gt; as a child of &lt;subst&gt;, without requiring both. This would allow
Un &lt;subst xml:id="s1" next="\#s2"&gt;&lt;del&gt;buon&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/subst&gt; padre &lt;subst xml:id="s2" prev="\#s1"&gt;&lt;add&gt;onesto&lt;/add&gt;&lt;/subst&gt;
rather than requiring something like
Un &lt;del xml:id="sp1"&gt;buon&lt;/del&gt; padre &lt;add xml:id="sp2"&gt;onesto&lt;/add&gt;
&lt;join targets="\#sp1 \#sp2" result="subst" scope="root"/&gt;

Syd, the example we discussed in the meeting is in the Genetic work group's document:

http://www.tei-c.org/Activities/Council/Working/tcw19.html\#index.xml-body.1\_div.3\_div.2\_div.6

The proposal is indeed to have both &lt;add&gt; and &lt;del&gt; in &lt;subst&gt;, but to be able to include text that may be between text that is marked as deleted, or added. You can see the full example \(with image\) in the link above, but the example encoding looks like this:

&lt;ge:line&gt;While &lt;subst&gt;
&lt;del&gt;pondering&lt;/del&gt; thus &lt;add&gt;she
mus'd&lt;/add&gt;
&lt;/subst&gt;, her pinions fann'd&lt;/ge:line&gt;

Right. My point is that TEI already supports one method of encoding this that makes it perfectly clear that “onesto” was substituted for “buon” and that “padre” was not part of this editorial intervention \(i.e., was not crossed out or supralinear or whatever\):

Un &lt;del xml:id="sp1"&gt;buon&lt;/del&gt; padre &lt;add xml:id="sp2"&gt;onesto&lt;/add&gt;
…
&lt;join targets="\#sp1 \#sp2" result="subst" scope="root"/&gt;

Would the example in the guidelines--the one from William James--violate the "one del, one add" rule anyway?:

One must have lived longer
with &lt;subst&gt;
&lt;del seq="1"&gt;this&lt;/del&gt;
&lt;del seq="2"&gt;
&lt;add seq="1"&gt;such
a&lt;/add&gt;
&lt;/del&gt;
&lt;add seq="2"&gt;a&lt;/add&gt;
&lt;/subst&gt; system, to appreciate its
advantages.

Looks to me like it would, but I admit that part of the discussion here is beyond me. 

Also, I'm not sure where to register these two other beefs, but since they came up as I was pondering this:

1\. In 11.3.5 SubstitutionsTEI: Substitutions, the text that introduces the code above is in error. Namely, in the phrase "the word this is first replaced by such a and this is then" the second "this" should not be italicized, as it refers not to the \*word\* this but is a pronoun for "such a." Right?

2\. On my project, we fairly frequently encounter pairs of words or phrases that we want corral together as alternatives to one another. In the most usual case, the first alternative is deleted and the second added, but quite often the first is not deleted. Because &lt;subst&gt; doesn't allow text, we have taken to using &lt;orig&gt; for the first reading. Lou's comment of 2010-05-01 made me realize, though, that this runs afoul of the stated intent for &lt;subst&gt;. None of the discussion or proposals to date seem to me to address the case I'm talking about, so perhaps it's just a red herring for this particular ticket?

\(Same as above with formatting fixed\)

In the P5 guidelines, the note on &lt;certainty&gt;'s @match attribute states: "The context for the pattern is the nodeset identified by the value of the target attribute. If no value is given for target, the context is the document root element." \(http://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-certainty.html\) We would like to suggest that the definition be changed so that in the absence of a @target defining the context, the default context is the &lt;certainty&gt; element itself. This would enable @match to use XPaths relative to the element to which it is attached, such as match=".." to refer to the parent of &lt;certainty&gt;. This is already legal if &lt;certainty&gt; has an @xml:id and @target points to it. So 

&lt;lem resp="7.18"&gt;σημ&lt;unclear&gt;α&lt;/unclear&gt;&lt;supplied reason="lost"cert="low"&gt;σί&lt;/supplied&gt;&lt;unclear&gt;α&lt;/unclear&gt;&lt;certainty xml:id="foo"target="\#foo" match=".." locus="value"/&gt;&lt;/lem&gt;

is currently perfectly in line with the guidelines \(see Lou Burnard's message in a thread on TEI-L: http://listserv.brown.edu/archives/cgi-bin/wa?A2=ind0909&L=TEI-L&T=0&F=&S=&P=15221\). Our suggestion would simplify

&lt;certainty xml:id="foo" target="\#foo" match=".." locus="value"/&gt;

to 

&lt;certainty match=".." locus="value"/&gt;

removing the need to generate xml:ids for every &lt;certainty&gt; element. Since the document root is easily referred to in an XPath expression \(i.e. "/"\) there is really no need to make it the default context, especially since this removes the ability easily to refer to other nodes in the document from the &lt;certainty&gt; element itself.
This change would require no schema alterations. The only change needed would be to the text of the guidelines. 

In the thread on TEI-L referenced above, Wendell Piez voiced some objections to the use of @match, based on its similarity to XSLT's @match, which can only contain absolute XPath patterns. The use of a new attribute \(perhaps @select, like XSLT @select\) was suggested, but since there is already a @select attribute in the att.global.linking module, we would prefer to modify the definition of TEI @match instead. A further note in the guidelines stating that TEI @match is not XSLT @match might be warranted.

Here is a complete example, where we define an element &lt;descripGrp&gt; which needs to refer to the TBX element &lt;note&gt; which clashes with TEI's &lt;note&gt;. The user has to know that the prefix "tbx\_" has been assigned to &lt;note&gt;.

&lt;elementSpec 
xmlns:rng="http://relaxng.org/ns/structure/1.0"
prefix="tbx\_"
mode="add"
ns="http://www.lisa.org/TBX-Specification.33.0.html"
ident="descripGrp"&gt;
&lt;desc&gt;Contains one &lt;gi&gt;descrip&lt;/gi&gt; element as well as additional child elements for
associated administrative information.&lt;/desc&gt;
&lt;classes&gt;
&lt;memberOf key="id"/&gt;
&lt;/classes&gt;
&lt;content preserveNames="true"&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="tbx\_descrip"/&gt;
&lt;rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="tbx\_descripNote"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="tbx\_admin"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="tbx\_adminGrp"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="tbx\_transacGrp"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="tbx\_note"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="tbx\_ref"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="tbx\_xref"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;/rng:zeroOrMore&gt;

&lt;/content&gt;
&lt;/elementSpec&gt;
&lt;elementSpec 
xmlns:rng="http://relaxng.org/ns/structure/1.0"
prefix="tbx\_"
mode="add"
ns="http://www.lisa.org/TBX-Specification.33.0.html"
ident="note"&gt;
&lt;desc&gt;Any kind of note. &lt;/desc&gt;
&lt;classes&gt;
&lt;memberOf key="idlang"/&gt;
&lt;/classes&gt;
&lt;content preserveNames="true"&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="tbx\_entity.noteText"/&gt;
&lt;/content&gt;
&lt;/elementSpec&gt;

I think the request can be catered for by more creative use of the URI scheme. There are three possibilities
a\) actually use URNs in their full raging glory, as in 
&lt;p facs="urn:www.ox.ac.uk:P45"&gt;Hello world&lt;/p&gt;

b\) invent an arbitrary schema, which means something to you:

&lt;p facs="oxpics:P45"&gt;Hello world&lt;/p&gt;

c\)  use  "tag URIs" as documented in RFC 4151 \(http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc4151.txt\)

&lt;p facs="tag:indiana.edu:P45:&gt;Hello world&lt;/p&gt;

None of these is quite ideal, but then neither is @facsKey.

I humbly submit that the existing @facs with its URI semantics is sufficient unto the day thereof.

My instinct, John, without having read the RFCs carefully yet, is that
1\) You are permitted to create a scheme of your own, but you can't guarantee that it is unique unless you register it, which is a big pain
2\) If you are inventing a scheme that is not supposed to be de-referenced, I would not be surprised if you can't register it, as there is already a scheme for such things \(tag:, Sebastian's \(c\)\)

Although it is a bit unweildy, the tag: URI scheme seems to do exactly what we want:

&lt;pb facs="tag:wwp.brown.edu,2010:/exhibits/images/f7p12" n="12"/&gt;

However, there is a problem. There are 2 places in the TEI Guidelines where use of this mechanism makes sense, but the attribute semantics preclude it:
url= of &lt;graphic&gt;
and
url= of &lt;moduleRef&gt;

\(I realize that this is above and beyond the original feature request, which the tag: scheme does solve\)

tickets.description:
Currently, there is no elegant or canonical way to specify a normalized representation of a non-Gregorian &lt;date&gt;.  @when and @when-iso both use Gregorian, which is fine for recent dates, but for work on \(e.g.\) pre-17thC sources there is usually no reason whatsoever why one would, or should, convert Julian dates into Gregorian; and in fact this can't be done in certain other cases where there is no accepted mapping to Gregorian, as for instance with ancient dates, or where the date is within a fictional context.  However, without a generic normalization attribute for non-Gregorian dates it becomes messy to sort dates.  &lt;orig&gt; and &lt;reg&gt; could do it, but are always going to be implementation-specific and are hardly elegant for such a potentially very common task.

I am proposing a general-purpose solution which would provide a very broad range of functionality as described by example below, and which would require a new attribute class under att.datable as follows:


att.datable.generic

@datingPoint  \[data.pointer, optional\]
supplies a pointer to some location defining a named point in time with reference to which the datable item is understood to have occurred. \[e.g., points to a taxonomy/category or event.\]

@datingMethod  \[data.pointer, optional\]
supplies a pointer to some location defining a calendrical system or other means of interpreting the value of @when-generic, @notBefore-generic, @notAfter-generic, @from-generic or @to-generic \(possibly with respect to @datingPoint\).

@period       \[Identical to the attribute in att.datable.w3c.\]

@when-generic, @notBefore-generic, @notAfter-generic, @from-generic, @to-generic  \[data.word, optional\]
supplies the value of the date or time in a standard form, e.g. yyyy-mm-dd, which can be an absolute or relative value depending on the presence of the other attributes.

Some examples:

&lt;date when-generic="0027" datingPoint="\#RamesesII" datingMethod="\#Egyptian365"&gt;27 years into the reign of Rameses II, counting in the Egyptian 365-day calendar&lt;/date&gt;

On the &lt;date when-generic="5" datingPoint="\#ArabianNights"&gt;5th night&lt;/date&gt;, Scheherazade told another story...

&lt;date when-generic="1590-02-20" datingMethod="\#JulianOS"&gt;The 20th Feb 1590 \(old style\)&lt;/date&gt; is &lt;date when-generic="1591-02-20" datingMethod="\#JulianNS"&gt;the 20th Feb 1591 \(new style\)&lt;/date&gt; in the Julian Calendar, according to the English custom.

We aim to sight land on the &lt;date when-generic="35" datingPoint="\#sailedSierraLeone" datingMethod="\#TravelItinerary"&gt;35th day&lt;/date&gt;.

In the last example, the targets of @datingPoint and @datingMethod might be as follows:

&lt;taxonomy xml:id="dating"&gt;
&lt;category xml:id="TravelItinerary"&gt;
&lt;gloss&gt;@when-generic indicates the number of days as an integer.&lt;/gloss&gt;
&lt;/category&gt;
&lt;/taxonomy&gt;
...
&lt;person xml:id="RevRichardMadox"&gt;
&lt;event xml:id="sailedSierraLeone" when-generic="193" datingPoint="\#sailedSouthampton" datingMethod="\#TravelItinerary"&gt;&lt;label&gt;sailed from Sierra Leone&lt;/label&gt;&lt;p&gt;This was 193 days after leaving Southampton.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/event&gt;
...
&lt;event xml:id="sailedSouthampton" when-iso="1582-01-01"&gt;&lt;label&gt;sailed from Southampton&lt;/label&gt;&lt;/event&gt;
&lt;/person&gt;

In addition to the above class att.datable.generic, it would be greatly advantageous if @calendar were available as part of att.datable.  Currently, it is only available for &lt;date&gt;, although there seems no reason why this should be the case.  It should be emphasized that it specifies the calendar system of the text within the given element rather than that of the attributes of the @when genus, to avoid confusion; however, in the absence of @datingPoint and @datingMethod it could, by convention, indicate the calendrical system used by @when-generic, e.g.
&lt;date when="1499-12-23" when-generic="1500-01-01" calendar="Julian"&gt;1st Jan 1500&lt;/date&gt;
&lt;date when="1499-12-23" when-generic="905 Jumada i-Ula 11" calendar="Islamic"&gt;905 Jumada i-Ula 11&lt;/date&gt;

As an aside, after discussion in the TEI-MS-SIG List, it seems likely that some people are currently using @when for Julian dates without realising that they are meant for Gregorian dates.  It would be helpful to specify this in the attribute &lt;desc&gt;, which is currently rather misleading.  Alternatively, @when might be renamed @when-w3c.

posts.text:
Outcome of the council meeting discussion on 2011-04-12:

We see the use-case and agree it needs to be served. Our final proposal is below, following a report on the discussion we had.

We discussed the possibility that we might need to distinguish between "standard" dating systems \(such as the Islamic calendar\) and "fictional" systems \(such as the Star Trek calendar\), but decided that this is not a meaningful distinction; all calendar systems are essentially fictional.

We discussed the proposal by Lou that all of this should be handled through the creation of a specialized element, but determined that this would be inadequate, because the requirement is to supply custom dating features for all the elements in att.datable, and to allow these to co-exist beside standardized dates expressed using the existing attributes.

Therefore we believe that there is a need for these attributes. However, we are unhappy with the use of "generic", since we believe this would be misleading; we would prefer "custom", because this would tend to discourage the accidental use of these attributes by someone who didn't really understand the difference between the various sets of dating attributes.

We like the @datingPoint and @datingMethod, as data.pointer, and suggest that the latter could be used \(and should probably be shown in the guidelines\) to point to the &lt;calendarDesc&gt; element which will probably arise out of ticket \#2994671.

So:

The following attribute class should be created:

att.datable.custom

It should be added to att.datable, alongside att.datable.w3c and att.datable.iso.

The following optional attributes should be added to the class, with a datatype of 1-to-infinity of data.word:

@when-custom
@from-custom
@to-custom
@notBefore-custom
@notAfter-custom

The following optional attributes should be added to the class, with a datatype of data.pointer:

@datingPoint
@datingMethod

In addition:

@calendar should be moved from att.date to att.datable.
@period should be moved from att.datable.w3c to att.datable.

Finally, a new section needs to be added to the Guidelines to explain the use of these attributes. This can only be accomplished once action has also been taken on ticket \#2994671 \(&lt;calendarDesc&gt;\). In the meantime, we should be collecting some plausible and real examples that demonstrate the variety of possible uses, building on what the submitter has already provided. I would suggest that we include examples from the Islamic calendar, at least one ancient calendar \(Egyptian?\), one Julian \(preferably one not easily normalized to Gregorian\), and one more obviously fictional \(Star Trek?\).

Following extensive discussion on tei-meta and elsewhere, the proposal is now 
\- to add new elements &lt;elementRef&gt;, &lt;classRef&gt; and \(probably\) &lt;macroRef&gt;
\- to add optional attributes @include and @exclude to &lt;moduleRef&gt;
\- to document more clearly the semantics of how these elements should work together

Council approved this basic set of modifcations at Dublin meeting.

tickets.description:
The &lt;zone&gt; element \(part of the &lt;facsimile&gt; family\) currently defines a rectangle on a &lt;surface&gt; by means of four attributes \(@ulx, @uly etc.\). There is general agreement among those working with &lt;facsimile&gt; that we need a way to define non-rectangular shapes on surfaces. This proposal is the simplest and most generally-liked option arising out of the recent long discussion on TEI-L and the graphics list.

@svg:points is a "list of points", defined here:

http://www.w3.org/TR/SVG/shapes.html\#PointsBNF&gt;

It's not really clear to me by what mechanism an attribute from the svg namespace could be added to a core TEI class when the facsimile module is loaded, though.

posts.text:
Discussion on the GRAPHICS SIG suggests that adding the attribute in a different namespace is actually not a good idea, for various reasons \(compatibility with DTDs, requirement for an extra file for XSD, treading on W3C toes by defining an attribute in the SVG namespace\). So the proposal is now:

add @points to att.coordinated, with a content model which is based on SVG @points:

http://www.w3.org/TR/SVG11/shapes.html\#PointsBNF

This definition can easily be reduced to a regular expression, and defined as a token in the same way that application/@version is defined:

http://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-application.html

\[example only\]
&lt;rng:data type="token"&gt;
&lt;rng:param name="pattern"&gt;\[\d\]+\[a-z\]\*\[\d\]\*\(\\.\[\d\]+\[a-z\]\*\[\d\]\*\)\{0,3\}&lt;/rng:param&gt;
&lt;/rng:data&gt;

token \{ pattern = "\[\d\]+\[a-z\]\*\[\d\]\*\(\\.\[\d\]+\[a-z\]\*\[\d\]\*\)\{0,3\}" \}
\[/example only\]

This is the pattern for the datatype, as a regexp \(according to me -- someone else like Syd should check it\):

\[\d\]+,\[\d\]+\(\[\s\]+\[\d\]+,\[\d\]+\)\{2,\}

With regard to defining a non-rectangular surface, we are saying that @ulx, @urx and friends are mandatory even when @points is provided, so there will always be a rectangular bounding box that serves as the coordinate space for both &lt;surface&gt; and &lt;zone&gt;. But I think the ability to use @points to define a non-rectangular area within &lt;surface&gt; is actually a nice side-effect of this proposal.

@points is always a supplement, never an alternative to @ulx etc.

tickets.description:
&lt;bibl&gt; has several potentially useful elements available to it,  
which don't seem to be available in &lt;biblStruct&gt;:

&lt;sponsor&gt;
&lt;funder&gt;
&lt;distributor&gt;
&lt;principal&gt;

These are certainly needed when citing projects, or multimedia publications which have distributors. &lt;distributor&gt; is a member of model.imprintPart, but that is not really useful if the document being cited is an online publication. I propose that:

&lt;distributor be added to model.respLike, which already contains &lt;principal&gt;, &lt;funder&gt; and &lt;sponsor&gt;; and 
model.respLike be added to &lt;analytic&gt;, &lt;monogr&gt; and &lt;series&gt;, so that these elements are available in &lt;biblStruct&gt; citations.

posts.text:
Acting on the decision of the Council at the April 2011 meeting, I've added &lt;distributor&gt; to model.respLike. However, I have not acted on the second recommendation from my October 2010 comment:

Replace explicit references to author | editor | respStmt in the
content model of biblStruct with a reference to the model.respLike class,
so that &lt;distributor&gt;, &lt;funder&gt;, &lt;sponsor&gt; and &lt;principal&gt; are available
where &lt;author&gt;, &lt;editor&gt; and &lt;respStmt&gt; currently are.

The committee initially approved this, but on further investigation there are some complexities that require more investigation before anything can be done here:

By &lt;biblStruct&gt;, we really mean &lt;analytic&gt;, &lt;monogr&gt; and &lt;series&gt;. &lt;analytic&gt; is straightforward; we simply replace this:

&lt;rng:ref name="author"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="editor"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="respStmt"/&gt;

with this:

&lt;rng:ref name="model.respLike"/&gt;

in the existing content model:

&lt;content&gt;
&lt;rng:zeroOrMore xmlns:rng="http://relaxng.org/ns/structure/1.0"&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="author"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="editor"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="respStmt"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="title"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="ref"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="date"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;/rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;/content&gt;

&lt;series&gt; is slightly more complicated, in that it has this for its content model:

&lt;content&gt;
&lt;rng:zeroOrMore xmlns:rng="http://relaxng.org/ns/structure/1.0"&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:text/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="model.gLike"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="title"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="ref"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="editor"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="respStmt"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="biblScope"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="model.global"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;/rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;/content&gt;

&lt;author&gt; is not there, of course; replacing &lt;editor&gt; and &lt;respStmt&gt; with model.respLike would have the side-effect of adding &lt;author&gt; as well as the other intended items \(&lt;sponsor&gt; etc.\).

&lt;monogr&gt; is the most complicated of all. Here we have a rather rigidly-controlled sequence and structure for the content model:

&lt;content&gt;
&lt;rng:group xmlns:rng="http://relaxng.org/ns/structure/1.0"&gt;
&lt;rng:optional&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:group&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="author"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="editor"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="respStmt"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="author"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="editor"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="respStmt"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;/rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:oneOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="title"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:oneOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="idno"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="editor"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="respStmt"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;/rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;/rng:group&gt;
&lt;rng:group&gt;
&lt;rng:oneOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="title"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="ref"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;/rng:oneOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="idno"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="author"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="editor"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="respStmt"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;/rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;/rng:group&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;/rng:optional&gt;
&lt;rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="model.noteLike"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="meeting"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;/rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="edition"/&gt;
&lt;rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="idno"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="editor"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="respStmt"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;/rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;/rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="imprint"/&gt;
&lt;rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="imprint"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="extent"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="biblScope"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;/rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;/rng:group&gt;
&lt;/content&gt;

The simplest way to proceed would be to replace every instance of editor and/or author and/or respStmt with model.respLike; this, again, would introduce &lt;author&gt; in a couple of contexts where it's currently excluded \(where &lt;idno&gt; shares a block with &lt;editor&gt; and &lt;respStmt&gt;\). We also have an explicit instance of &lt;meeting&gt;, which is also a member of model.respLike.

The committee will revisit this in the future, so the ticket remains open.

tickets.description:
In order to allow the cit element to document the encoding of possible linguistic examples together with the excerpt it self, egXML, which can be seen as a kind of exemplifying quotation should be part of the content model of cit. 
This is a use case that occurs quite regularly in the ISO/TC 37/SC 4 document, such as below, taken from ISO-TimeML:
&lt;cit xml:id="cit2a" type="example" n="2"&gt;
&lt;q&gt;John left on 31 December 2007.&lt;/q&gt;
&lt;egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"&gt;
&lt;isoTimeML xml:id="a1"&gt; John &lt;EVENT eid="e1" eiid="ei1"
type="transition" tense="past"&gt;left&lt;/EVENT&gt;
&lt;SIGNAL xml:id="s1"&gt;on&lt;/SIGNAL&gt;
&lt;TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="date" value="2007-12-31"&gt;31
December 2007&lt;/TIMEX3&gt;
&lt;/isoTimeML&gt;
&lt;/egXML&gt;
&lt;/cit&gt;
a more ellaborated example could be:
&lt;cit type="example" xml:id="cit15b" n="15"&gt;
&lt;q xml:lang="zn"&gt;我吃过饭了。&lt;/q&gt;
&lt;cit type="translation"&gt;
&lt;q xml:lang="en"&gt;I have had/had my dinner.&lt;/q&gt;
&lt;/cit&gt;
&lt;q&gt;
&lt;egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"&gt;
&lt;EVENT xml:id="e1" target="\#token1 \#token2" pred="EAT"
class="OCCURRENCE" type="TRANSIATION" pos="VERB" tense="NONE"
aspect="PERFECTIVE" polarity="POS"/&gt;
&lt;/egXML&gt;
&lt;/q&gt;
&lt;/cit&gt;

Hi,
this is just a request to allow more markup to come through on the div headings and numbering to make it a bit easier to manipulate the CSS stylesheets.

1\. Currently the numbering is just concatenated with the &lt;head&gt; info into a single &lt;h..&gt; tag which makes it hard to pick out the number to construct fancier headings with the stylesheet. e.g. having the each chapter \(in a more traditional text\) headed with something like "Chapter 1" in one font size and style and the actual heading in a different style.

2\. The concatenation behaviour also makes it difficult to markup and style div headings that have a more complex structure. For instance I've been marking up a text in which for the most part each chapter has a single title but there are a couple which are quotes followed by the name of the individual source of the quote. In the original print edition the source was set in smaller type beneath the quote. In my original markup I had used to &lt;head&gt; tags one set as type="sub". In the output this becomes concatenated into a single tag and you can't separate the sources name. In an attempt to get around this I resorted to \(what is probably better markup\) placing a &lt;quote&gt; and &lt;bibl&gt; tag inside the &lt;head&gt; tag like:

&lt;head&gt;&lt;quote&gt;&lt;p&gt;And I Came into the Fields and Wide Palaces of Memory&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;bibl&gt;&lt;name&gt;St Augustine&lt;/name&gt;&lt;/bibl&gt;&lt;/quote&gt;&lt;/head&gt;

unfortunately all the markup was stripped out of the heading so I'm not able to get to it with a style sheet.

3\. It doesn't appear to be possible to have a &lt;div&gt; without a heading. The script cleverly tries to construct one using the the type="" tag or failing that out puts the tag name i.e. "div" as the title. I've tried adding empty &lt;head&gt; tags but this doesn't work. There are some structures where you need to suppress the title, I'm not sure whether this is a problem with the way OxygenXML interprets the "teilite.rng" file but you need to use unheaded &lt;div&gt; tags to work around the fact that you can't have &lt;p&gt; tags after and embedded &lt;div&gt; e.g.

&lt;div type="chapter"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;introduction and commentary&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div type="letter"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;content&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;this tag which might contain summarizing commentary is not allowed...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div&gt; 
&lt;p&gt;it has to be embedded like this&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

In this case you don't want a heading. in the final div tag.

Thanks
Gary

posts.text:
Hi,
I've been playing around with SVN revision 7857 and have noted the changes to heading number - thanks for that. After fiddling around I also found it useful to put a space instead of a '.' for the numberSpacer parameter to suppress the '." at the end of the number.

I'm not sure if I understand your changes about the heading tags though. I haven't noticed any change in the behaviour for multiple &lt;heads&gt;. With this tag set up

&lt;div type="chapter"&gt;
&lt;head&gt;And I Came into the Fields and Wide Palaces of Memory&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;head type="sub"&gt;St Augustine&lt;/head&gt;
...

I get

&lt;h3&gt;&lt;span class="headingNumber"&gt;3.23. &lt;/span&gt;And I Came into the Fields and Wide Palaces of Memory St Augustine
&lt;/h3&gt;

If I change the first &lt;head&gt; to 
&lt;head type="main"&gt;And I Came into the Fields and Wide Palaces of Memory&lt;/head&gt;

I get
&lt;h3 class=" main"&gt;&lt;span class="headingNumber"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;And I Came into the Fields and Wide Palaces of Memory St Augustine
&lt;/h3&gt;

I'm not getting a separate &lt;head&gt; tag for St Augustine. \(there's also an extra space in front of 'main'\)

I also noticed if I have this tag set up with embedded tags in the &lt;head&gt;


&lt;head&gt;&lt;quote&gt;&lt;p&gt;And I Came into the Fields and Wide Palaces of Memory&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;bibl&gt;&lt;name&gt;St Augustine&lt;/name&gt;&lt;/bibl&gt;&lt;/quote&gt;&lt;/head&gt;

I get this

&lt;h3&gt;&lt;span class="headingNumber"&gt;3.23. &lt;/span&gt;And I Came into the Fields and Wide Palaces of Memory
&lt;span id="index-name-d26e3357"&gt;
&lt;\!--anchor1--&gt;&lt;/span&gt;St Augustine
&lt;/h3&gt;

with an "empty" span with an index id in it.

Thanks
Gary

We've been using markup like this:

&lt;availability status="restricted"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
&lt;ref type="license" target="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/"&gt;
&lt;graphic url="http://i.creativecommons.org/l/by-nc-sa/3.0/88x31.png"/&gt;
Distributed by the University of Oxford under a Creative Commons
Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported License&lt;/ref&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/availability&gt;

which seems to do the job, and is typically verbose hard-to-parse TEI.

since this request does even have an owner, I think it needs more debate

@license would be optional, not mandatory, right?

It's not the TEI way to supply a URL but not provide lots of prose describing what's at that URL in case the target disappears.  So it seems we should recommend that a prose description of what's at the URL be included in a &lt;p&gt; inside of &lt;availability&gt;.

In any case, the Oxford encoding method strikes me as just as processable as @license.

The ISO 24612 document shows an example of such usage, here within an &lt;a&gt; \(annotation node\) element:
&lt;a xml:id="de6" label="vchunk" ref="vc-n10" as="xces"&gt;
&lt;fs&gt;
&lt;f name="voice"&gt;active&lt;/f&gt;
&lt;f name="tense"&gt;SimPre&lt;/f&gt;
&lt;f  name="type"&gt;FVG&lt;/f&gt;
&lt;/fs&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

tickets.description:
I'd like to suggest that the origDate element be extended to allow a child element certainty or precision. As recently defined, it's now very convenient to use @match='..' on these elements to refer to the status of some aspect of their parent element, and origDate is certainly an element that it is often necessary to qualify what one says about a particular aspect of \(which end of a data-span is precise and which approximate, for example\).

Example of usage:

&lt;origDate notBefore="0212" notAfter="0300"&gt;
Probably third century, and certainly after the Citizenship Edict of Caracalla.
&lt;precision match="../notBefore" degree="1"/&gt;
&lt;precision match="../notAfter" degree="0.25"/&gt;
&lt;/origDate&gt;

posts.text:
I suggested &lt;list&gt; but another possibility would be grouping elements, say, &lt;traitGrp&gt;, &lt;stateGrp&gt;, and &lt;eventGrp&gt; with useful attributes such as att.canonical. Then I could do something like this:

&lt;person&gt;
...
&lt;stateGrp&gt;
&lt;occupation&gt;Tinker&lt;/occupation&gt;
&lt;occupation&gt;Tailor&lt;/occupation&gt;
&lt;/stateGrp&gt;
...
&lt;/person&gt;

Another possibility would be to allow traitlike, statelike, and eventlike elements to contain themselves:

&lt;occupation&gt;
&lt;occupation&gt;Soldier&lt;/occupation&gt;
&lt;occupation&gt;Sailor&lt;/occupation&gt;
&lt;/occupation&gt;

tickets.description:
As it stands, &lt;precision&gt; only allows the encoder to use numbers such as @degree and @stdDeviation to describe precision. Such a description fails when no such numbers can be inferred; e.g. "c. 1450 AD" or "about seventy." I therefore request an attribute that allows a textual description of precision to be made. Perhaps it could be called @grade? These examples could then be encoded as:

&lt;date xml:id="d001" when="1450"&gt;c. 1450&lt;/date&gt;
&lt;precision target="\#d001" grade="circa"/&gt;

&lt;num xml:id="n001" value="70"&gt;about 70&lt;/num&gt;
&lt;precision target="\#n001" grade="about"/&gt;

posts.text:
Not sure if this fills a need that can not already be met by the use of the @cert attribute or the certainty/precision elements. Could you not tag your examples as:

&lt;num min="10" max="12" cert="95%&gt;
&lt;num min="20" max="30" cert="medium"&gt;
?

tickets.description:
It would be good to have a way of typing &lt;figure&gt;s.

Examples:

&lt;figure type="map"&gt;
&lt;head&gt;Back Bay West&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;graphic url="boston-bbw.png"/&gt;
&lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;figure type="photograph"&gt;
&lt;head&gt;The Country Club, Brookline, 1882&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;p&gt;America's earliest country recreational and social club. The core of the clubhouse was built in 1802 \[…\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/figure&gt;

Example use cases \(from a processing application perspective\):
. generate separate lists of maps, illustrations, etc.
. collect all //figure\[@type='photograph'\] and display in a gallery
. print-to-web conversion project: for each figure\[@type='map'\] as encountered in the print edition, render a dynamic map \(e.g. via Google Maps API\) instead of the printed map image

Note: if &lt;figure&gt; were to be a member of att.typed, there would be obvious uses of @subtype as well. Consider:

&lt;figure type="map" subtype="political"/&gt;
&lt;figure type="map" subtype="orthophoto"/&gt;
&lt;figure type="map" subtype="road"/&gt;

These may have to be rendered using different applications and/or data sources depending on @subtype.

Possibly related: FR 1274137

