tickets.description:
New element &lt;document&gt; to be added to model.resourceLike ; new element &lt;line&gt; to be added to model.zonePart; new element &lt;patch&gt; 
allowed within &lt;surface&gt;. Together with existing &lt;surface&gt; and &lt;zone&gt; elements, these allow theory-neutral transcription of the physicality  of  document.

Justification, element specs, and examples are in the Genetic WG document at http://www.tei-c.org/Activities/Council/Working/tcw19.html \(derived from http://tei.svn.sourceforge.net/viewvc/tei/trunk/genetic/\)

Section 4.3.2 \(\#DSFLT\) says, "The floatingText  element should only be used for complete texts which form a part of the text being encoded."  Why the prohibition against using this element for incomplete portions of texts?  Is it because it's too hard to draw a line between a whole text and a few words in order to decide at what point your encoding warrants inclusion use of &lt;floatingText&gt; instead of just &lt;q&gt;?

By prohibiting its use when encoding all but a complete text, we make it impossible to encode the structure of a quoted text beyond elements available within &lt;quote&gt;.  You can't encode various epistolary elements \(dateline, salutation, etc.\), title page elements, or other things available only within floatingText.

By analogy, we trust people to decide when to use

&lt;rs&gt;John Smith&lt;/rs&gt;

and when to use

&lt;rs&gt;
&lt;persName&gt;
&lt;forename&gt;John&lt;/forename&gt;
&lt;surname&gt;Smith&lt;/surname&gt;
&lt;/persName&gt;
&lt;/rs&gt;

so I think we can trust them to use &lt;floatingText&gt; only when warranted.

posts.text:
This is an example we were discussing on the Music SIG list and involves the new element requested in FR 3086726.

&lt;music type="notation"&gt;
&lt;ptr target="happybirtday.xml" mimeType="application/vnd.recordare.musicxml"/&gt;
&lt;/music&gt;

This specifies that the pointed xml has to be considered a MusicXML \(and not, say, MEI\) file by the parser, either for content negotiation or for further manipulation of the XML once retrieved.

By interleave, I mean if elements A B and C are members of class M, then : putting &lt;ref name="M\_interleave"/&gt; yields &lt;interleave&gt;
&lt;ref name="A"/&gt;
&lt;ref name="B"/&gt;
&lt;ref name="C"/&gt;
&lt;/interleave&gt;. That is, A B and C must be present in any order. I used that for metada components in which  elements had to be there \(with the "good" cardinalities\) but wanted to relax somehow the order.
Rq : in practice, you have to produce :
&lt;interleave&gt;
&lt;group&gt;
&lt;ref name="A"/&gt; \{n, m\}
&lt;/group&gt;
&lt;group&gt;
&lt;ref name="B"/&gt; \{p, q\}
&lt;group&gt;
&lt;ref name="C"/&gt; \{r, s\}
&lt;/group&gt;
&lt;/interleave&gt;

if you mix the cardinalities with this. That is you get any order provided the A's are grouped together, the B's are also grouped and the C's as well \(this seems a relaxNG limitation\). Therefore : BBB AAA CC is OK but ABACAB is not.

tickets.description:
Greg Murray at the University of Virginia Library explained in an email to Kevin on 2008-12-02 that he invented the element name &lt;cols/&gt; when setting up Virginia's vendor specs but has regretted the name since.  It would be more consistent with other TEI element names to use &lt;colShift cols="\_\_\_"/&gt; instead of &lt;cols n="\_\_\_"/&gt; because:

a\) it is consistent with other TEI element names like &lt;shift/&gt; and &lt;handShift/&gt;

b\) it avoids confusion with the name of the cols= attribute already used for &lt;table&gt;

c\) it better indicates the purpose of the element--to mark a change in columnar layout within a div.

posts.text:
This solves some but not all problems of libretto-like texts. A musical number might involve one or more speakers. The critical thing is that it is a more "closed" form relative to its surroundings. That is why it is typically announced by a head-like text such as "Air" or "Recitative and Aria"  The "set-offness" could be modeled as 
&lt;q&gt;&lt;label&gt;Air&lt;/label&gt;
&lt;sp&gt;&lt;speaker&gt;Jack&lt;/speaker&gt;
&lt;lg&gt;
&lt;l&gt;&lt;/&gt;
&lt;l&gt;&lt;/l&gt;
&lt;/lg&gt;&lt;/sp&gt;
&lt;sp&gt;&lt;speaker&gt;Jill&lt;/speaker&gt;
&lt;lg&gt;
&lt;l&gt;&lt;/&gt;
&lt;l&gt;&lt;/l&gt;
&lt;/lg&gt;&lt;/sp&gt;
&lt;/q&gt;

How's the following as an update to &lt;egXML&gt;:

&lt;attList&gt;
&lt;attDef ident="valid"&gt;
&lt;desc&gt;indicates the intended validity of the example with respect to
a schema.&lt;/desc&gt;
&lt;valList&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="yes"&gt;&lt;desc&gt;the example is intended to be fully valid,
assuming that its root example can be used as the root element of the
schema concerned.&lt;/desc&gt;&lt;/valItem&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="feasibly"&gt;&lt;desc&gt;the example could be transformed into
a valid document by inserting any number of valid attributes and child
elements anywhere within it; it is valid against a version of the
schema concerned in which every data, list, element, or attribute
element has been made optional.&lt;/desc&gt;
&lt;/valItem&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="no"&gt;&lt;desc&gt;the example is not intended to be valid,
and contains deliberate errors.&lt;/desc&gt;&lt;/valItem&gt;
&lt;/valList&gt;
&lt;/attDef&gt;&lt;/attList&gt;


&lt;exemplum&gt;
&lt;egXML xml:lang="und" xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples" valid="feasible"&gt;
&lt;TEI &gt;
&lt;teiHeader xml:lang="fra"&gt;
&lt;\!-- ... --&gt;
&lt;/teiHeader&gt;
&lt;text xml:lang="eng"&gt;
&lt;\!-- ... --&gt;
&lt;/text&gt;&lt;/TEI&gt;&lt;/egXML&gt;

&lt;/exemplum&gt;

tickets.description:
Under some circumstances, one does a bibliographical entry as
a &lt;biblStruct&gt;, in others as a &lt;biblFull&gt;. Inside both you get to 
talk about a "series", using  &lt;series&gt; or &lt;seriesStmt&gt;. Yet the beasts
are rather different in their content.

&lt;series&gt;         allows \(simplified\)     \text   | title    | ref    | editor    | respStmt    | biblScope
&lt;seriesStmt&gt; allows \(simplified\)     model.pLike | title | idno | respStmt 

This should be more aligned than it is: 

1\. one has plain text, the other has &lt;p&gt;
2\. one permits &lt;idno&gt;, the other &lt;biblScope&gt;
3\. one allows editor | respStmt, the other only respStmt

the examples we have show &lt;idno&gt; and &lt;biblScope&gt; being used for the same purpose:

series:
&lt;title level="s"&gt;Serie A: Historische Quellenkunden&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;biblScope&gt;Band 11&lt;/biblScope&gt;

seriesStmt:

&lt;title&gt;Machine-Readable Texts for the Study of Indian Literature&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;idno type="vol"&gt;1.2&lt;/idno&gt;

I propose that we change &lt;seriesStmt&gt; to have a content model of


&lt;choice xmlns="http://relaxng.org/ns/structure/1.0"&gt;
&lt;oneOrMore&gt;
&lt;ref name="model.pLike"/&gt;
&lt;/oneOrMore&gt;
&lt;group&gt;
&lt;oneOrMore&gt;
&lt;ref name="title"/&gt;
&lt;/oneOrMore&gt;
&lt;zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;choice&gt;
&lt;ref name="editor"/&gt;
&lt;ref name="respStmt"/&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;
&lt;/zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;ref name="biblScope"/&gt;
&lt;/zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;/group&gt;
&lt;/choice&gt;


or similar

If you want a make a macro which defines a set of fixed choices, the TEI &lt;valList&gt; is a more natural tool than plain RNG, allowing as it does for the documentation desc/gloss elements. However, &lt;macroSpec&gt; does not permit use of &lt;valList&gt;.

I propose that the content model of macroSpec be changed to .. &lt;rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;rng:choice&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="stringVal"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="content"/&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="valList"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:choice&gt;
&lt;/rng:zeroOrMore&gt;

... to allow macro content models to be closer to element content models.

data.sex is an example of a macro which would benefit

