This is an essential feature for all kinds of annotations where the markables are to be identified as groups of non sequential objects on the primary document. I am currently finalizing the ISO document on morphosyntactic annotation and would like to put in a recommendation on the identification of word-forms on top of a tokenized input as follows:

&lt;p&gt;
&lt;w xml:id="w1"&gt;I&lt;/w&gt;
&lt;w xml:id="w2"&gt;wanna&lt;/w&gt;
&lt;w xml:id="w3"&gt;put&lt;/w&gt;
&lt;w xml:id="w4"&gt;up&lt;/w&gt;
&lt;w xml:id="w5"&gt;new&lt;/w&gt;
&lt;w xml:id="w6"&gt;wallpaper&lt;/w&gt;
&lt;pc&gt;.&lt;/pc&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;spanGrp type="wordForm"&gt;
&lt;span target="\#w1" ana="\#fs1" corresp="\#entry1"/&gt;
&lt;span target="\#w2" ana="\#fs2" corresp="\#entry2"/&gt;
&lt;span target="\#w2" ana="\#fs3" corresp="\#entry3"/&gt;
&lt;span target="\#w3 \#w4" ana="\#fs4" corresp="\#entry4"/&gt;
&lt;span target="\#w5" ana="\#fs5" corresp="\#entry5"/&gt;
&lt;span target="\#w6" ana="\#fs6" corresp="\#entry6"/&gt;
&lt;/spanGrp&gt;


Note that this should work exactly in the same way for: "I want to put new wall paper up" \(disjoint "put up"\)

tickets.description:
currently a &lt;table&gt; may have a &lt;head&gt;, but it does not support the idea of a trailer or footer, which is a fairly common facility in table modelling languages.
An example of when its needed comes from EEBO A04863, where the text at the bottom
self-identifies as being part of the table

&lt;table&gt;
&lt;head&gt;The Table of Battallions, reduced out of the grand square of men.&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;row&gt;
&lt;cell&gt;1&lt;/cell&gt;
&lt;cell&gt;2&lt;/cell&gt;
&lt;cell&gt;3&lt;/cell&gt;
&lt;cell&gt;4&lt;/cell&gt;
&lt;/row&gt;
&lt;row&gt;
&lt;cell&gt;841&lt;/cell&gt;
&lt;cell&gt;3&lt;/cell&gt;
&lt;cell&gt;289 289 256&lt;/cell&gt;
&lt;cell&gt;7&lt;/cell&gt;
&lt;/row&gt;
&lt;trailer&gt;The end of the Table of Battallions reduced out of the battels of g. and squares of men: vpon the right side of euery leafe.&lt;/trailer&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

The TCP folks have used &lt;trailer&gt; here, but we could use something else, or define a &lt;foot&gt;

posts.text:
@kshawkin: I'm not sure what &lt;head&gt; inside &lt;person&gt; means. \(Though I see some lovely opportunities for jokes here...\)

I think I was thinking about the alternative between structured and unstructured metadata object records.  i.e. with &lt;place&gt; I can have:
&lt;place&gt;
&lt;head&gt;My favourite Place&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;p&gt; Some paragraphs about it&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;note&gt;Some notes about it&lt;/note&gt;
&lt;idno&gt;An idno&lt;/idno&gt;
&lt;/place&gt;

With &lt;person&gt; you can basically do the same, but don't have the category of information:
\( model.noteLike | model.biblLike | idno | linkGrp | link \)\*,
\( model.placeLike | listPlace \)\*
which can appear after the paragraphs.

We can have paragraphs inside &lt;person&gt; but should you be able to have a note, bibl, or idno after those paragraphs?

-James

with the proviso that no-one \(I assume\) yet points to an ODD from an instance;
so a processing XSLT will not have access to the information in the use case you note. also bearing in mind that tests about "am I inline" often involve a contextual test

but the general utility is good.

I am removing myself from this, as there is no action at present. It needs a face to face debate,
and a decision between the many ways of implementing the functionality. As MH and BB note, the existing class mechanism would do the job just as well,  though it does not solve the contextual problem.

ideas of a standardized TEI "processing model" are highly contentious :-\}

I am mostly inclined to agree with Lou about the "if it aint broke" viewl;
however, we do expose our  source tree, and we have been pillored in public
for using entity refs there, so I claim there is a case to answer.

Yep, @rend should be used. The existing mix of semantics and presentation misled me. 

What about replacing the current list with "ordered", "unordered", "gloss" and "runon"? I can't think what "simple" would indicate. If there is one high-level semantic difference in lists, surely it is between those that are ordered and those that are unordered. 

Examples in the Guidelines sometimes use @rend="runon", but "runon" does have semantic import. It says: This list is embedded in the grammatical structure of what surrounds it.

The difference between

&lt;list type="ordered&gt;
&lt;head&gt;First Presidents of the United States&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;item&gt;Washington&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;Adams&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;Jefferson&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;/list&gt;

and 

On those remote pages it is written that animals are divided into &lt;list&gt;
&lt;item n="a"&gt;those that belong to the Emperor, &lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item n="b"&gt;embalmed ones, &lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item n="c"&gt;those that are trained, &lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item n="d"&gt;suckling pigs.&lt;/item&gt;&lt;/list&gt;

is more than presentational.

Even my list \(\!\) isn't orthogonal though. You could have an ordered or unordered glossary, ordered or unordered runon. So maybe there should be one attribute @ordered that just indicates "ordered" / "unordered", those being the only allowed values, one of them being the default; then another unconstrained attribute for type.

I see that other listLike elements make no mention of these types.

I ended up doing this in CSS, in this order:

\[display='list-item'\]\[hasNumber\]     \{list-style-type:none\}        /\* the @n gets used instead \*/
\[tei="list"\]                                \{list-style-type:square\}
\[tei="list"\]\[type="ordered"\]                \{list-style-type:decimal\}
\[tei="list"\]\[type="bulleted"\]               \{list-style-type:disc\}
\[tei="list"\]\[type="simple"\]                 \{list-style-type:none\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="armenian"\]              \{list-style-type:armenian\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="circle"\]                \{list-style-type:circle\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="cjk-ideographic"\]       \{list-style-type:cjk-ideographic\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="decimal"\]               \{list-style-type:decimal\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="decimal-leading-zero"\]  \{list-style-type:decimal-leading-zero\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="georgian"\]              \{list-style-type:georgian\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="hebrew"\]                \{list-style-type:hebrew\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="hiragana"\]              \{list-style-type:hiragana\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="hiragana-iroha"\]        \{list-style-type:hiragana-iroha\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="katakana"\]              \{list-style-type:katakana\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="katakana-iroha"\]        \{list-style-type:katakana-iroha\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="lower-alpha"\]           \{list-style-type:lower-alpha\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="lower-greek"\]           \{list-style-type:lower-greek\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="lower-latin"\]           \{list-style-type:lower-latin\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="lower-roman"\]           \{list-style-type:lower-roman\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="none"\]                  \{list-style-type:none\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="square"\]                \{list-style-type:square\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="upper-alpha"\]           \{list-style-type:upper-alpha\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="upper-latin"\]           \{list-style-type:upper-latin\}
\[tei="list"\]\[rend\*="upper-roman"\]           \{list-style-type:upper-roman\}

tickets.description:
@scheme on &lt;keywords&gt; allows for reference to an external or internally defined keyword scheme used for the various &lt;term&gt; elements inside &lt;keywords&gt;.  I'm interested in attaching keywords to a TEI document that are not from a controlled vocabulary, such as author-defined keywords. In such a case, I would be inclined to do:

&lt;keywords&gt;
&lt;term&gt;ceremonials&lt;/term&gt;
&lt;term&gt;fairs&lt;/term&gt;
&lt;term&gt;street life&lt;/term&gt;
&lt;/keywords&gt;

without using @scheme.  Lou agreed with this approach on TEI-L:

http://listserv.brown.edu/archives/cgi-bin/wa?A2=TEI-L;bf8f0a5e.1208

In fact, P4 did not require @scheme, so we would be going back to the glory days.

There are a few problems with section 3.11.2.3 and the content models of associated elements:

1\) Not much guidance is given on when to put &lt;biblScope&gt; in which parent element.

2\) When guidance is given, it's for journal articles \(to put volume and issue number in &lt;biblScope&gt;s &lt;imprint&gt;\), but the information there doesn't "relat\[e\] to the publication or distribution of a bibliographic item", as &lt;imprint&gt; is currently defined.

To address \(1\), we propose to explain more explicitly in the Guidelines that &lt;biblScope&gt; be used to constrain the scope \(within the parent element of the biblScope\) of the item cited in the next lowermost "level", where "level" is used as in section 3.11.2.1. Take this example:

&lt;biblStruct&gt;
&lt;analytic&gt;
&lt;author&gt;Albert Schachter&lt;/author&gt;
&lt;title&gt;Iolaos&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;/analytic&gt;
&lt;monogr&gt;
&lt;title&gt;Herakles to Poseidon&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;imprint&gt;&lt;date&gt;1986&lt;/date&gt;&lt;/imprint&gt;
&lt;biblScope type="pp"&gt;64-70&lt;/biblScope&gt;
&lt;/monogr&gt;
&lt;monogr&gt;
&lt;title&gt;Cults of Boiotia&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;imprint&gt;&lt;pubPlace&gt;London&lt;/pubPlace&gt;&lt;/imprint&gt;
&lt;extent&gt;4 vols.&lt;/extent&gt;
&lt;biblScope type="part"&gt;2&lt;/biblScope&gt;
&lt;/monogr&gt;
&lt;series&gt;
&lt;title&gt;Bulletin of the Institute of Classical Studies
Supplements&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;biblScope type="vol"&gt;38&lt;/biblScope&gt;
&lt;/series&gt;
&lt;/biblStruct&gt;

There are four "levels": the lowest "level" is the &lt;analytic&gt;, the next is the first &lt;monogr&gt;, then the second &lt;monogr&gt;, and finally the highest "level" is &lt;series&gt;.  The article "Iolaos" appears on pp. 64-70 of \*Herakles to Poseidon\*, which is part 2 of \*Cults of Boiotia\*, which is vol. 38 of \*BICS  Supplements\*.

Each &lt;biblScope&gt; describes where \(within its parent element\) to find the thing in the previous level.

To address \(2\), we would remove the current recommendation in 3.11.2.3 to use monogr/imprint/biblScope for journal articles and instead say to encode information like volume, issue, and date of a given journal issue as a child of &lt;monogr&gt;.  We would modify examples accordingly, and we would deprecate use of &lt;biblScope&gt; inside of &lt;imprint&gt;.

There would be no change to the definition or examples of &lt;extent&gt;: it would still be used not for mentions of particular pages or volumes but for a statement like "4 vols." and "325 pages".

posts.text:
Agree to create &lt;citedRange&gt; with optional @type:

&lt;bibl&gt;&lt;ptr target="\#mueller01"/&gt;, &lt;citedRange target="http://example.com/mueller3.xml\#page4"&gt;vol. 3, pp. 4-5&lt;/citedRange&gt;&lt;/bibl&gt;

Content model of &lt;citedRange&gt; is to be determined.  Probably start with just text for now.

tickets.description:
The annotation of documents using standoff annotations is a very useful and flexible methodology. Nevertheless, TEI does not have any specific elements for encoding this information.
In most of cases, the standoff annotations are stored as external TEI files linked to the text being annotated. Nevertheless, this way of storing the standoff annotations is very rigid and presents numerous problems, for example, for indexing or searching the corpus of documents using the information of the annotations. In these cases, it would be very useful to have the standoff annotations INSIDE the TEI documents being annotated \(\!\!\!\). 

Therefore, it is suggested to include define a new set of TEI elements specifically dedicated to the encoding of the standoff annotations.

The idea would be to store the standoff annotations between the &lt;teiHeader&gt; and the &lt;text&gt;, following the same philosophy as used for the &lt;facsimile&gt; and for &lt;sourceDoc&gt; \(in some way these two elements could also be considered as a "type" of annotation\).

For the standoff annotation, the structure could be:

&lt;TEI&gt;
&lt;teiHeader&gt;
...
&lt;/texHeader&gt;
&lt;standoff&gt;
\[information of the annotations\]
&lt;/standoff&gt;
&lt;text&gt;
...
&lt;/text&gt;
&lt;/TEI&gt;

This structure would provide the extra advantage of allowing to annotate the information at different TEI levels in a natural manner. So for more complicated TEI documents having different hierarchical levels, the standoff annotations could be encoded as follows:

&lt;teiCorpus&gt;
&lt;teiHeader&gt;
...
&lt;/teiHeader&gt;
&lt;TEI&gt;
&lt;teiHeader&gt;
...
&lt;/texHeader&gt;
&lt;standoff&gt;
...
&lt;/standoff&gt;
&lt;text&gt;
...
&lt;/text&gt;
&lt;/TEI&gt;
&lt;TEI&gt;
&lt;teiHeader&gt;
...
&lt;/texHeader&gt;
&lt;standoff&gt;
...
&lt;/standoff&gt;
&lt;text&gt;
...
&lt;/text&gt;
&lt;/TEI&gt;
&lt;/teiCorpus&gt;

This structure would also provide the extra advantage of allowing to annotate, not only the text of the document, but also the metadata of the different hierarchical levels of the TEI document.

The specific encoding of the annotations inside &lt;standoff&gt; could be as follows:

&lt;standoff&gt;
&lt;annotation type="..." subtype="..."&gt;
&lt;author&gt;...&lt;/author&gt;
&lt;date&gt;...&lt;/date&gt;
&lt;ptr&gt;...&lt;/ptr&gt;
\[other data needed\]
&lt;/annotation&gt;
&lt;/standoff&gt;

As a last remark it is also suggested to allow inside the &lt;annotation&gt; the TEI element &lt;figure&gt; in order to facilitate the annotation not only of textual information, but also of images and formulas.

Conclusion: the proposed structure for the encoding of standoff annotations in TEI provides the following advantages:

\- allows to encode standoff annotations under TEI in a natural manner, which is not the case at the moment
\- allows to store the standoff annotations INSIDE the TEI document being annotated in a specific location, facilitating the     process of indexing and    
searching said documents
\- it is naturally integrated in the hierarchical structure of the TEI \(&lt;teiCorpus&gt;, &lt;TEI&gt;\)
\- allows to annotate both, the textual and not textual information, and also the metadata of the &lt;teiHeader&gt;
\- facilitates the exchange of annotations because they are already stored in the original TEI document being annotated

Remark: this idea has been already suggested by Piotr Bański in his article "Why TEI stand-off annotation doesn't quite work and why you might want to use it nevertheless", in http://www.balisage.net/Proceedings/vol5/html/Banski01/BalisageVol5-Banski01.html

posts.text:
I would tend to put it as a new element between the &lt;teiHeader&gt; and the &lt;text&gt;, similarly to the &lt;facsimile&gt; or &lt;sourceDoc&gt;. The following reasons:
1\) I wouldn't include the stand-off annotations as part of the teiHeader, because teiHeader must supply the descriptive and declarative information making up an electronic title page prefixed to every TEI-conformant text.The stand-off annotations comprise "extra" information, like the annotations themselves, that are not part of the text being described or metadata associated to it.
Therefore, in order to clarify this difference I would suggest to put the annotations outside the &lt;teiHeader&gt;

2\) I woudn't include the stand-off annotations as part of the text, because the &lt;text&gt; contains a single text of any kind, whether unitary or composite, for example a poem or drama, a collection of essays, a novel, a dictionary, or a corpus sample. In this case the stand-off annotations are text but not the text being encoded, but metadata and text related to the text being encoded. Therefore, in order to clarify this difference I would suggest to put the annotations outside the &lt;text&gt;

Taking these reasons into account, I would tend to think that the best place for the standoff annotations \(metadata + text associated to the text being encoded\) would be in a new "area"between the &lt;teiHeader&gt; and the &lt;text&gt;. This is similar to the idea of, for example, &lt;facsimile&gt; which contains information that is nor directly the text being encoded neither its metadata, but a new "object" related to said text, i.e. the information about the facsimile of the text.

tickets.description:
When encoding in TEI documents having a big amount of metadata, it is very often needed to group the metadata in groups, so the data can be organized in a easy and intuitive manner.

The TEI standards already offer some elements designed to group specific type of elements, for example:

\- &lt;group&gt;: contains the body of a composite text, grouping together a sequence of distinct texts.
\- &lt;castGroup&gt;
\- &lt;lg&gt; \(line group\)
\- &lt;surfaceGrp&gt; 
\- &lt;altGrp&gt; 
\- &lt;gramGrp&gt;
\- &lt;interpGrp&gt;
\- &lt;joinGrp&gt;
\- &lt;linkGrp&gt;
\- &lt;locusGrp&gt;
\- &lt;measureGrp&gt;
\- &lt;personGrp&gt;
\- &lt;rdgGrp&gt;
\- &lt;relationGrp&gt;
\- &lt;spanGrp&gt;

Nevertheless, these "grouping elements" are restricted to only one type of elements to be grouped and do not allow to mix different elements under the same group.
Furthermore, the fact of having already so many different "grouping elements" directed to different specific elements shows the need of defining a generic mechanism to group the TEI elements.

Therefore, it is proposed to create a TEI element \(for example &lt;grp&gt;\) that allows to logically group any set of TEI elements.
For example:

&lt;grp&gt;
&lt;"element1"&gt;
&lt;"element2"&gt;
&lt;"element3"&gt;
&lt;/grp&gt;

For example, one could need to group a set of organizations to which a certain document has some type of relationship.
In this case, it could be useful to group said set of organizations as a group in the metadata associated to the TEI document:

&lt;grp type="organizations"&gt;
&lt;orgName&gt;...&lt;/orgName&gt;
&lt;orgName&gt;...&lt;/orgName&gt;
&lt;orgName&gt;...&lt;/orgName&gt;
&lt;/grp&gt;

This element would be extremely useful when encoding in TEI documents comprising a big amount of metadata associated to them \(elements in the &lt;teiHeader&gt;.

posts.text:
Hi,
many thanks for your reply. I will try to provide an example where it could be more clearly identified the need of the proposed &lt;grp&gt; element.
This element will be very useful for documents having a lot of metadata that must be encoded in the header of the document or other parts \(like &lt;facsimile&gt; for example\). This element would also prepare the TEI standards to encode not only the textual information of a document but also information stored in databases, stylesheets, etc... 
In all these cases, it is needed to define a type of hierarchy between the different encoded elements.

Lets take the following example: 
Currently TEI defines the element &lt;linkGrp&gt; \(link group\) that defines a collection of associations or hypertextual links.

&lt;linkGrp type="translation"&gt;
&lt;link target="\#CCS1 \#SW1"/&gt;
&lt;link target="\#CCS2 \#SW2"/&gt;
&lt;link target="\#CCS \#SW"/&gt;
&lt;/linkGrp&gt;

The point is that, in specific cases, it is needed to define a collection of links and corresponding titles.
In such a case I would need to group NOT links together but  sets of &lt;link&gt;+&lt;title&gt; together:

&lt;grp&gt;
&lt;link/&gt;
&lt;title&gt;...&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;/grp&gt;
&lt;grp&gt;
&lt;link/&gt;
&lt;title&gt;...&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;/grp&gt;
&lt;grp&gt;
&lt;link/&gt;
&lt;title&gt;...&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;/grp&gt;


Also another example: I have a document and I would like to encode this document in TEI but I also would like to keep track of certain metadata associated to the document, for example classifications in different schemas associated to this document grouped by country.
Normally, the classification of the document can be encoded as:

&lt;textClass&gt;
&lt;catRef target="\#..."/&gt;
&lt;classCode scheme="http://www.udcc.org"&gt;001.9&lt;/classCode&gt;
&lt;keywords scheme="http://authorities.loc.gov"&gt;
&lt;list&gt;
&lt;item&gt;End of the world&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;History - philosophy&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;/list&gt;
&lt;/keywords&gt;
&lt;/textClass&gt;

The problem is that I cannot group the different classifications by, for example, country. Depending on the specific needs and the original encoding, this could be very useful. Having a &lt;grp&gt; element it would be very easy:

&lt;grp type="us\_classes"&gt;
&lt;textClass&gt;...&lt;/textClass&gt;
&lt;textClass&gt;...&lt;/textClass&gt;
&lt;textClass&gt;...&lt;/textClass&gt;
&lt;/grp&gt;
&lt;grp type="eu\_classes"&gt;
&lt;textClass&gt;...&lt;/textClass&gt;
&lt;textClass&gt;...&lt;/textClass&gt;
&lt;/grp&gt;

Actually the solution would be to encode the country information in each &lt;textClass&gt; but then it would be very difficult to organize the metadata information in a hierarchical manner.
There are many other possible examples, as many as different specific needs of the encoding.

What lies behind the &lt;grp&gt; request is to allow the use of TEI for organizing the metadata associated to a document according to the user's needs.

To take your first example, grouping links with titles: wouldn't it be easier to use a &lt;list&gt;, like this?

&lt;list&gt;
&lt;item&gt;&lt;title&gt;...&lt;/title&gt;&lt;link/&gt;&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;&lt;title&gt;...&lt;/title&gt;&lt;link/&gt;&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;&lt;title&gt;...&lt;/title&gt;&lt;link/&gt;&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;/list&gt;

Many thanks for your reply \(\!\)
The point is that, for example, in the solution of:
&lt;list&gt;
&lt;item&gt;&lt;title&gt;...&lt;/title&gt;&lt;link/&gt;&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;&lt;title&gt;...&lt;/title&gt;&lt;link/&gt;&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;&lt;title&gt;...&lt;/title&gt;&lt;link/&gt;&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;/list&gt;

...it looks a bit "artificial" because, for example, if one would also need to define for each group &lt;title&gt;&lt;link/&gt; a list of authors and associated addresses \(for example\) then I would again need to define a new &lt;list&gt;&lt;item&gt; structure.

In fact, the solution you proposed is at this moment the only way of grouping sets of elements \(grouping them under &lt;item&gt;\). Defining the element &lt;grp&gt; it would allow us to define ANY hierarchy for storing the metadata \(\!\!\) what would provide the TEI a very powerful tool for the future encoding of documents having a big amount of metadata.

Without an element like &lt;grp&gt; we are very constraint when defining the hierarchy of the metadata as we desire and this is VERY IMPORTANT for example when we want to store the metadata in an EFFICIENT MANNER to implement the SEARCHING of the documents 
For example, citing again the same example, for increasing the searching speed in certain applications, it could be more efficient to store the metadata as:

&lt;grp type="us\_classes"&gt;
&lt;textClass&gt;...&lt;/textClass&gt;
&lt;textClass&gt;...&lt;/textClass&gt;
&lt;textClass&gt;...&lt;/textClass&gt;
&lt;/grp&gt;
&lt;grp type="eu\_classes"&gt;
&lt;textClass&gt;...&lt;/textClass&gt;
&lt;textClass&gt;...&lt;/textClass&gt;
&lt;/grp&gt;

...rather than using attributes type and subtype.

This is at the end the GREAT advantage of having &lt;grp&gt; element, it would ALLOW the developers to encode the metadata in the MOST EFFICIENT MANNER for processes like searching, without constraints.

TEI is VERY POWERFUL for encoding text and more and more other non-textual objects, but in order to take full advantage of it, it is also needed that it allows to also FLEXIBLE encode data like stand-off annotations and other type of metadata associated to the text but not necessary related to the textual contains \(e.g. organizational aspects, administrative information, document flow management...\). For allowing this further step in TEI, I think an element like &lt;grp&gt; would be extremely useful.

I don't actually see what efficiency is to be gained from using a &lt;grp&gt; rather than @type. With the proper indexes defined, and XML database should find this:

//textClass\[@type='us'\]

just as quicly as this:

//grp\[@type='us\]//textClass

In discussion with Martin Holmes, we considered that &lt;ref&gt; might be more useful, so that you could include the transcription in the element as well as the normalized number in @target, e.g.

&lt;ref target="tel:+1-201-555-0123"&gt;\(201\) 555 0123&lt;/ref&gt;
or even:
&lt;ref target="tel:+1-201-555-0834"&gt;\(201\) 5550 TEI&lt;/ref&gt;

Would this be contained in addrLine, presumably?

this isn't as easy as it sounds. I assumed you are talking about the suggested list of values for div/@type in eg section 4.5, for sections of the front matter. Unfortunately, we don't have a notation for this situation in ODD, ie a &lt;valLlst&gt; which applies only in a  particular context. I am reluctant to just copy over the prose from the chapter.

I am not sure those suggested lists of values for @type are very helpful anyway. Its amusing to see that most of the examples don't follow them.

I am marking this as Rejected, but still open, so feel free to prove me wrong :-\}

tickets.description:
I suggest this addition to the Guidelines 3.2.1:

White space is allowed and therefore significant between elements within &lt;name&gt;, &lt;persName&gt;, &lt;orgName&gt;, and &lt;placeName&gt;. Therefore

&lt;persName&gt;
&lt;foreName&gt;Mary&lt;/foreName&gt;
&lt;forename&gt;Ann&lt;/forename&gt;
&lt;nameLink&gt;De&lt;/nameLink&gt;&lt;surName&gt;Mint&lt;/surName&gt;
&lt;/persName&gt;

encodes "Mary Ann DeMint" and

&lt;persName&gt;
&lt;foreName&gt;Mary&lt;/foreName&gt;&lt;foreName&gt;Ann&lt;/forename&gt;
&lt;nameLink&gt;De&lt;/nameLink&gt;
&lt;surName&gt;Mint&lt;/surName&gt;
&lt;/persName&gt;

encodes "MaryAnn De Mint".

posts.text:
Nesting &lt;forename&gt; might be useful in some situations, but white space is significant within it, too. So the same care is required with &lt;forename&gt; as with &lt;name&gt;, &lt;persName&gt;, &lt;orgName&gt;, and &lt;placeName&gt;.

&lt;forename&gt;
&lt;forename&gt;Mary&lt;/forename&gt;
&lt;forename&gt;Ann&lt;/forename&gt;
&lt;/forename&gt;

encodes " Mary Ann "

&lt;forename&gt;&lt;forename&gt;Mary&lt;/forename&gt;
&lt;forename&gt;Ann&gt;&lt;/forename&gt;&lt;/forename&gt;

encodes "Mary Ann"

&lt;forename&gt;&lt;forename&gt;Mary&lt;/forename&gt;&lt;forename&gt;Ann&gt;&lt;/forename&gt;&lt;/forename&gt;

encodes "MaryAnn"

Or, strictly, the first and second both encode Mary on one line and Ann on another. But virtually all downstream processors will convert that carriage return to a space, even though neither TEI nor XML specs say they must or even should.

For full treatment of the trickiness here, see http://wiki.tei-c.org/index.php/XML\_Whitespace.

The @when part of a &lt;date&gt; can of course include a time, so &lt;time&gt; is strictly redundant, unless you want to say something like &lt;time&gt;teatime&lt;/time&gt;

It doesn't seem totally implausible that the time should form part of a publication date, so Kevin's option \(c\) does not appeal to me. I think adding an example using one would be a good idea. I am agnostic about whether or not we need to mention &lt;time&gt; in the &lt;specList&gt; : as Kevin says, there are other elements which we don't mention. 

Maybe what is needed is the ability to specify a model  class \(and its members\) within a specList?

